1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:02,080
(ORDERS SHOUTED IN GERMAN)

2
00:00:10,840 --> 00:00:12,680
Look at them.

3
00:00:12,680 --> 00:00:14,840
Couldn't march their way
out of a paper bag.

4
00:00:16,640 --> 00:00:21,480
Strange, isn't it? Hitler said
there'd be a thousand of us. In the
end, he couldn't even manage 30.

5
00:00:22,040 --> 00:00:25,320
Not the most glorious episode
in military history, I'd say.

6
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,200
Do you think
we'll be hanged or shot?

7
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:34,600
Mind you, in Carrington's case,
it might be neither.

8
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:36,760
He might get lucky
and die of the clap first.

9
00:00:39,240 --> 00:00:41,920
Are you talking to me today?
Which would you choose?

10
00:00:43,800 --> 00:00:46,760
Hanging or shooting?
I'm all for hanging. It's quieter.

11
00:00:49,040 --> 00:00:51,960
Strange, isn't it?
The two of us ending up here.

12
00:00:53,160 --> 00:00:56,000
We could start a reunion club.
Hang together.

13
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:56,200
# Muss i' denn, muss i' denn

14
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:58,960
# Muss i' denn, muss i' denn

15
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:02,480
# Zum Staedtele hinaus,
Staedtele hinaus

16
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:05,320
# And du mein Schatz
bleibst hier... #

17
00:01:05,320 --> 00:01:07,240
(CHATTER, LAUGHTER)

18
00:01:09,840 --> 00:01:11,920
(LAUGHS) Bis spaeter.

19
00:01:11,920 --> 00:01:13,800
Ja?

20
00:01:14,200 --> 00:01:18,440
What did I tell you? One of the
most beautiful cities in Europe!

21
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:21,520
And some of the most beautiful
women.

22
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:23,920
(AIR-RAID SIRENS)
Life isn't too bad.

23
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:27,520
It's a raid.
Huh?

24
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:29,680
No. They're on their way
somewhere else.

25
00:01:32,320 --> 00:01:34,240
James, let's eat.

26
00:01:38,160 --> 00:01:40,240
(AEROPLANE ENGINES)

27
00:01:40,240 --> 00:01:42,120
(EXPLOSION)

28
00:01:43,280 --> 00:01:45,400
(RUMBLING)

29
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:47,360
(EXPLOSION)

30
00:01:47,360 --> 00:01:49,200
MAN: Hilfe! Hilfe!

31
00:01:52,280 --> 00:01:54,680
(SHOUTING, SCREAMING, EXPLOSIONS)

32
00:01:56,840 --> 00:01:59,200
(SCREAMS DISTORT AND FADE)

33
00:02:34,240 --> 00:02:36,320
DS McDonald.
DI Jones.

34
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:38,440
How do you do?
DI Morgan.

35
00:02:38,440 --> 00:02:40,200
Sergeant Rowle.
How do you do?

36
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:41,680
Sergeant Parrs.

37
00:02:41,680 --> 00:02:43,520
Mr Foyle. Yes.
I'm DCS Clarkeson.

38
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:46,560
I know who you are. How do you do?
Pleased to meet you. Come in.

39
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:50,480
I'm here to replace you. Well,
so I understand. What kept you?

40
00:02:50,480 --> 00:02:55,280
You'll be pleased to hear,
everything's in order. It's in my
report. I'll leave that there.

41
00:02:55,280 --> 00:03:00,040
It doesn't mention that anything
related to current investigations
you'll find in this office here.

42
00:03:00,520 --> 00:03:05,200
Pre-war and war-time records
are kept next door. Ask the desk
sergeant. He'll be happy to help.

43
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:09,040
I think that's about it.
Erm...congratulations on the post.

44
00:03:09,040 --> 00:03:11,960
Or commiserations, whichever
you think is appropriate.

45
00:03:11,960 --> 00:03:14,640
And...jolly good luck. Er -
Pleasure to meet you. Goodbye.

46
00:03:20,160 --> 00:03:22,080
Good luck, sir.

47
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:41,640
I've now had the opportunity
to examine your accounts,
Mr Wainwright.

48
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:43,680
Here we have your outgoings.

49
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:46,280
General expenses,
salaries, supplies, etc.

50
00:03:47,080 --> 00:03:49,560
And here we have payments in.

51
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:54,240
It would seem
this is not a felicitous time

52
00:03:54,240 --> 00:03:57,000
for the catering and hotel business
in Hastings.

53
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,640
Things are bound to pick up
eventually, Mr Harmworth.

54
00:03:59,640 --> 00:04:01,600
That MAY be the case,

55
00:04:01,600 --> 00:04:04,480
but here you are, asking us
to extend your overdraft limit.

56
00:04:04,480 --> 00:04:06,520
Just for a few months.

57
00:04:06,520 --> 00:04:09,400
You've overstepped that limit
on three occasions.

58
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:13,280
I see no evidence here
that your situation will improve
in the near future.

59
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:16,040
Well, it can't get any worse!

60
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,720
I wish I shared your confidence,
Miss Stewart.

61
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:22,400
I'm sorry.
Not only can the bank not help you,

62
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:26,080
but I must ask you
to take immediate steps
to clear your existing overdraft...

63
00:04:27,280 --> 00:04:30,200
..taking whatever actions
are necessary.

64
00:04:30,200 --> 00:04:32,080
Thank you.

65
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,680
Good day.

66
00:04:40,120 --> 00:04:43,040
I'm sorry, Sam.
Don't be.

67
00:04:43,040 --> 00:04:46,760
No. You don't understand. I won't
be able to pay you this month.

68
00:04:46,760 --> 00:04:48,480
Well, that's OK.

69
00:04:48,480 --> 00:04:51,240
You didn't pay me last month,
so it's not as if I'll notice.

70
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:53,200
You are a sport.

71
00:04:53,200 --> 00:04:56,200
We'll make a go of it somehow.
I know we will.

72
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:58,680
What shall we do now?
Cup of tea at Lyons?

73
00:04:58,680 --> 00:05:00,560
No. We ought to get back.

74
00:05:01,880 --> 00:05:05,240
Sometimes I wish the whole bloody
guesthouse would just...

75
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:07,720
I don't know, disappear.

76
00:05:07,720 --> 00:05:09,760
You ought never
to have taken it on.

77
00:05:09,760 --> 00:05:12,640
I had this romantic view
it would sort of run itself.

78
00:05:12,640 --> 00:05:15,000
Instead it's been
an absolute nightmare.

79
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,480
The only good thing
to come out of it is...well...

80
00:05:19,160 --> 00:05:21,120
..meeting you.

81
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:25,320
Ah...
Oh, sod it. Let's go to Lyons.

82
00:05:25,320 --> 00:05:28,160
Can we afford it?
We can go halves on a currant bun.

83
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:29,920
(LAUGHS)

84
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:35,720
Here you are, Christopher. I had
a devil of a job getting them.

85
00:05:35,720 --> 00:05:38,200
I managed to square the visa
with the Americans,

86
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:41,000
but, as for the Queen Mary,
she's been requisitioned.

87
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:43,160
For military and naval use only.
Mm-hm?

88
00:05:43,160 --> 00:05:47,520
I could've tried sending you
as a GI bride. I don't think
it would've worked. I wonder why!

89
00:05:47,520 --> 00:05:49,880
So what has happened?
I had a word with the MOI.

90
00:05:49,880 --> 00:05:52,160
You're departing Southampton
on the 17th.

91
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:53,960
If anyone asks,

92
00:05:53,960 --> 00:05:56,520
you're on a sponsored lecture tour,
all right? Fine.

93
00:05:56,520 --> 00:05:58,560
Remember, it's my neck on the line.

94
00:05:58,560 --> 00:06:00,520
I will. I'm grateful.

95
00:06:00,520 --> 00:06:02,720
Thank you.

96
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:06,000
There are times when I really don't
understand you. Why's that?

97
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,400
The war is finally,
completely over.

98
00:06:08,400 --> 00:06:11,680
The Japanese surrender. This
new bomb they're talking about...

99
00:06:11,680 --> 00:06:15,520
Makes me feel like we're entering
a new world. I'd agree.

100
00:06:15,520 --> 00:06:17,680
But you refuse to let go
of the old one.

101
00:06:17,680 --> 00:06:19,960
Unfinished business?
I thought you'd retired.

102
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:22,240
Oh, not quite the case. Resigned.

103
00:06:22,240 --> 00:06:26,760
Well, take care. America may not
take too kindly to an ex-detective
chief superintendent from Hastings

104
00:06:27,760 --> 00:06:30,240
sniffing around,
asking awkward questions.

105
00:06:30,240 --> 00:06:32,240
I'll take the chance.

106
00:06:32,240 --> 00:06:34,520
Well then, good luck.
Thank you.

107
00:06:41,160 --> 00:06:44,840
Late edition! Read all about it!
Devereaux stands trial for treason.

108
00:07:46,120 --> 00:07:47,960
Mr Foyle, sir.
Oh.

109
00:07:47,960 --> 00:07:50,160
How do you do?
How do you do?

110
00:07:50,160 --> 00:07:52,760
Please sit down, Mr Foyle.
Thank you.

111
00:07:52,760 --> 00:07:55,600
Have you been offered tea?
I won't, thank you very much.

112
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:57,800
Let's get straight to the point,
then.

113
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:00,840
You want to talk to me about
my client, James Devereaux.

114
00:08:00,840 --> 00:08:04,040
Well, not so much about him as
the unit he belonged to in Germany.

115
00:08:04,040 --> 00:08:06,320
The British Free Corps?
That's right.

116
00:08:06,320 --> 00:08:09,560
How much do you know about them?
Not as much as we'd like to.

117
00:08:09,560 --> 00:08:13,360
A meeting with your client
could prove enormously helpful.
How much do you know?

118
00:08:13,360 --> 00:08:16,280
It was just a propaganda exercise,
really, wasn't it?

119
00:08:16,280 --> 00:08:18,480
One of Hitler's crazier ideas.

120
00:08:18,480 --> 00:08:21,920
Get a bunch of misfits and
ne'er-do-wells out of the POW camps,

121
00:08:21,920 --> 00:08:26,920
dress them up in German uniforms
with Union Jacks, send them off
to fight against the Russians.

122
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:29,760
My client was picked up in Dresden,
what was left of it.

123
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:33,600
For a few months he was missing,
believed dead, then the Russians
handed him over.

124
00:08:33,600 --> 00:08:36,280
I may as well tell you now...

125
00:08:37,280 --> 00:08:39,920
..it's almost certain he'll hang.

126
00:08:39,920 --> 00:08:42,440
We're talking about traitors,
Mr Foyle.

127
00:08:42,440 --> 00:08:44,600
William Joyce, Lord Haw-Haw.

128
00:08:44,600 --> 00:08:49,800
John Amery, son of the Secretary
of State for India. (CHUCKLES)
The whole lot of them.

129
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:52,880
They're only getting what they
deserve. I think you'd agree.

130
00:08:52,880 --> 00:08:56,560
There are those who think that
a series of trials, treason trials,

131
00:08:56,560 --> 00:09:00,240
could be counterproductive. And
you've been asked to look into it.

132
00:09:00,240 --> 00:09:02,400
Well, I could try
to arrange a meeting,

133
00:09:02,400 --> 00:09:05,720
but, I should warn you now, it may
be a complete waste of time.

134
00:09:05,720 --> 00:09:07,640
He refuses to talk to me.
Not a word.

135
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:12,320
Perhaps he feels
you've given up on him.

136
00:09:13,280 --> 00:09:17,080
He's given up on himself.
It's almost as if he wants to die.

137
00:09:18,880 --> 00:09:23,680
Well, far be it for me
to stand in the way of the police
or the intelligence services.

138
00:09:23,680 --> 00:09:25,600
I'll see what I can do.

139
00:09:27,800 --> 00:09:29,720
Thank you.

140
00:09:32,200 --> 00:09:34,760
He...he did join the Nazis,
Mr Foyle.

141
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:37,680
He's admitted to it.

142
00:09:37,680 --> 00:09:39,920
And for what it's worth,

143
00:09:39,920 --> 00:09:42,960
I'd try to defend him
if he'd let me, but he won't.

144
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:45,840
There's really nothing more
I can do.

145
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:49,240
Right.

146
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:16,120
She's upstairs, sir.

147
00:11:22,880 --> 00:11:25,080
Sir.

148
00:11:25,080 --> 00:11:29,440
Ah. She's been strangled, sir,
with a nylon stocking.

149
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:31,880
I bet you she'd been saving it up
for after the war.

150
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:37,880
Does she have a name?
Agnes Lyttleton.

151
00:11:37,880 --> 00:11:40,960
She rents the room from
a Mrs Ramsay. She's downstairs.

152
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:45,480
Who found her?
She did. Mrs Ramsay.

153
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:50,240
So, what do you think, sir?

154
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:53,760
Boyfriend comes home, finds her
canoodling with some Yank?

155
00:11:53,760 --> 00:11:55,640
It wouldn't be the first time.

156
00:12:11,600 --> 00:12:16,320
I can't believe such a thing
could happen in my home.
I just can't believe it.

157
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:18,320
When did you know
something was wrong?

158
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:20,280
Well, this morning.

159
00:12:20,280 --> 00:12:24,200
She didn't come down for breakfast
and...I thought she'd overslept.

160
00:12:24,200 --> 00:12:26,040
Were you here last night?

161
00:12:26,040 --> 00:12:28,320
No. I was playing bridge
with some friends.

162
00:12:28,320 --> 00:12:30,560
I didn't arrive home
until about ten o'clock.

163
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:35,400
I was here,
in the house last night,

164
00:12:35,400 --> 00:12:37,280
and all the time she was...

165
00:12:41,040 --> 00:12:43,920
You want some more tea?
No.

166
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:45,760
No, thank you.

167
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:48,040
(Thank you...)

168
00:12:48,040 --> 00:12:51,640
Erm...did she have a job?
Did she work here in Brighton?

169
00:12:51,640 --> 00:12:53,440
Just outside.

170
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:57,160
White Friars. I'm sure you know it.
The family estate of the Devereaux.

171
00:12:58,080 --> 00:13:01,120
Did she have any friends?
Or any visitors?

172
00:13:01,120 --> 00:13:03,000
She did have a friend. Erm...

173
00:13:04,080 --> 00:13:06,400
Sylvie, I think her name was,
a stablegirl.

174
00:13:07,560 --> 00:13:11,160
And there was a young man, but he
was a prisoner of war in Germany.

175
00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:13,680
He wrote to her regularly, though.
Oh.

176
00:13:13,680 --> 00:13:17,440
Most of the prisoners of the German
camps have returned home now.

177
00:13:18,320 --> 00:13:20,480
He hasn't been here?
No.

178
00:13:20,480 --> 00:13:24,560
Miss Lyttleton would have asked me
first. She was that sort of girl.
Very considerate.

179
00:13:24,560 --> 00:13:26,440
Mrs Ramsay...

180
00:13:29,160 --> 00:13:31,080
What can you tell me about this?

181
00:13:32,760 --> 00:13:35,280
Isn't that the frame
from her...her bedroom?

182
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:37,680
It is, yes.

183
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:41,240
But...the photograph is missing.

184
00:13:41,240 --> 00:13:44,000
Do you know who the photograph
was of? Did you see it?

185
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:47,600
It wasn't my habit to enter
her room, but I did glimpse it.

186
00:13:47,600 --> 00:13:50,680
A young man in uniform. I can't
tell you much more than that.

187
00:13:50,680 --> 00:13:52,560
Where do you think it's gone?

188
00:14:18,240 --> 00:14:21,360
Cor! Quite a place, sir.

189
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:24,520
It certainly is.
To live somewhere like this,

190
00:14:24,520 --> 00:14:26,600
you wouldn't even know
there's been a war.

191
00:14:28,280 --> 00:14:31,720
Dreadful thing to have happened,
and I'm very sorry to hear it.

192
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:33,800
Agnes was a very pleasant girl.

193
00:14:33,800 --> 00:14:36,080
I can't imagine
anyone would want to hurt her.

194
00:14:36,080 --> 00:14:38,640
I'm afraid I can't help you,
Detective Inspector.

195
00:14:38,640 --> 00:14:42,680
I engaged Miss Lyttleton
nine months ago, to help me
with a project I'm working on.

196
00:14:42,680 --> 00:14:45,400
What is that, sir?
A history of the Devereaux family.

197
00:14:45,400 --> 00:14:49,840
It required a considerable amount
of research. Been here long, sir?

198
00:14:50,160 --> 00:14:53,280
We were given this land
by William the Conqueror.

199
00:14:53,280 --> 00:14:56,280
Miss Lyttleton worked here
for six hours a day.

200
00:14:56,280 --> 00:15:00,360
Excellent shorthand,
very diligent. Apart from that,
I know nothing about her at all.

201
00:15:00,360 --> 00:15:03,000
What about her family or friends?

202
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:05,920
Mr Milner, she was my secretary,
not my confidante.

203
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:08,880
And, apart from that, I have
absolutely nothing more to say.

204
00:15:08,880 --> 00:15:10,920
Jane?

205
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:13,280
Please excuse me, gentlemen.

206
00:15:26,400 --> 00:15:28,320
Detective Inspector!

207
00:15:31,760 --> 00:15:35,160
I'm very sorry, the way
my husband spoke to you just now.

208
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:39,480
He didn't mean to be rude,
but you've come
at a very difficult time.

209
00:15:39,480 --> 00:15:43,760
He has a son...
who's in a great deal of trouble.

210
00:15:43,760 --> 00:15:47,720
Please don't ask me to explain,
but you have no idea
how ill it's made him.

211
00:15:47,720 --> 00:15:52,160
And if he spoke off-handedly,
I can only apologise on his behalf.

212
00:15:52,160 --> 00:15:56,120
"HE has a son..." I take it that
he's not your son, Mrs Devereaux?

213
00:15:56,120 --> 00:15:58,400
No. I'm Charles's second wife.

214
00:15:58,400 --> 00:16:02,120
He lost his first wife, Caroline,
almost 20 years ago.

215
00:16:02,120 --> 00:16:04,600
And Agnes Lyttleton?

216
00:16:04,600 --> 00:16:07,680
I'm afraid I can't tell you much
about her. We hardly spoke.

217
00:16:07,680 --> 00:16:09,960
She was living with
our housekeeper, Mrs Ramsay.

218
00:16:10,760 --> 00:16:14,760
Mrs Ramsay works here?
She used to. She's retired.

219
00:16:14,760 --> 00:16:19,560
Miss Lyttleton had always lived in
Brighton, at least for the last few
years, but her house was bombed.

220
00:16:19,880 --> 00:16:23,120
She needed somewhere to live, so
we recommended her to Mrs Ramsay.

221
00:16:23,120 --> 00:16:25,000
Thank you.

222
00:16:38,520 --> 00:16:41,040
Gentleman to see Prisoner 484.

223
00:16:51,040 --> 00:16:52,960
(KEYS JANGLE)

224
00:16:58,800 --> 00:17:00,720
(GATE CLOSES)

225
00:17:01,960 --> 00:17:03,600
Hello.

226
00:17:07,040 --> 00:17:09,120
The name's Foyle.
Did they tell you who I am?

227
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:15,840
I understand
you were reluctant to see me.
Thank you for agreeing anyway.

228
00:17:17,680 --> 00:17:19,600
Anything to get out of my cell.

229
00:17:20,520 --> 00:17:22,200
Ah, I see.

230
00:17:22,200 --> 00:17:24,800
Did they tell you why I'm here?

231
00:17:24,800 --> 00:17:28,560
You're a policeman. You want to
know about the British Free Corps.

232
00:17:28,560 --> 00:17:30,520
That's about the strength of it,
yes.

233
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:32,360
Do you mind if I sit down?

234
00:17:39,440 --> 00:17:41,360
Erm...what can you tell me?

235
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:52,960
I understand why you don't want
to talk. Not a pleasant subject.
But you have agreed to see me.

236
00:17:52,960 --> 00:17:57,000
I've nothing to read.
The people here aren't chatty.
I don't get many visitors.

237
00:17:58,280 --> 00:18:00,240
Right.

238
00:18:00,240 --> 00:18:01,920
No family?

239
00:18:02,960 --> 00:18:04,920
I don't want to see my family.

240
00:18:04,920 --> 00:18:06,840
Why would that be?

241
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:17,200
Listen, there's an understanding
that there are various reasons

242
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:20,240
why people are or have become
Nazi sympathisers.

243
00:18:20,240 --> 00:18:22,640
In the case of members
of the British Free Corps,

244
00:18:22,640 --> 00:18:27,040
it seems important to establish to
what extent that sympathy is genuine

245
00:18:27,040 --> 00:18:30,040
or to what extent coercion has been
involved. Why did you join?

246
00:18:31,440 --> 00:18:34,400
Are you sorry the Germans lost,
that Hitler's dead?

247
00:18:34,400 --> 00:18:36,760
Did you want them to win?
I don't care who won.

248
00:18:36,760 --> 00:18:38,800
Is that really the case?

249
00:18:38,800 --> 00:18:41,440
Thousands of people dead.
Everywhere burnt out.

250
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:43,320
Theatres, museums, all rubble.

251
00:18:44,800 --> 00:18:46,320
What difference does it make?

252
00:18:48,600 --> 00:18:51,960
Is this Dresden you're talking
about? I understand you were there.

253
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:56,120
I was in a lot of places.

254
00:18:57,520 --> 00:18:59,760
Dunkirk, as well, I gather,

255
00:18:59,760 --> 00:19:02,640
and...served with distinction,
according to your men.

256
00:19:10,440 --> 00:19:13,360
So it's very difficult
for someone like me to understand

257
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:15,640
why you'd find yourself
in this position

258
00:19:15,640 --> 00:19:18,920
and why you'd choose
to die in such a useless way.

259
00:19:18,920 --> 00:19:20,760
What makes you think it's useless?

260
00:19:22,240 --> 00:19:25,200
I was told you wanted to ask
about the British Free Corps.

261
00:19:25,200 --> 00:19:27,560
All you've done is
ask questions about me.

262
00:19:30,480 --> 00:19:32,680
I don't know you.
I don't need to talk to you.

263
00:19:34,880 --> 00:19:36,800
Please, just go away.

264
00:19:44,640 --> 00:19:46,560
(KEYS JANGLE)

265
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:13,560
(BIRDSONG)

266
00:20:18,840 --> 00:20:21,560
Ah! I see you! I see you!

267
00:20:21,560 --> 00:20:23,360
(LAUGHS)
I see you!

268
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:30,080
OK, you got me,
you got me, you got me!

269
00:20:40,680 --> 00:20:42,600
(AIRCRAFT, EXPLOSIONS)

270
00:20:45,040 --> 00:20:47,120
(SIRENS)

271
00:20:47,120 --> 00:20:49,840
(EXPLOSIONS, SCREAMING)

272
00:20:57,200 --> 00:21:00,720
So...did you get
the information you wanted?

273
00:21:02,400 --> 00:21:04,480
Any idea what happened to him
in Dresden?

274
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:06,720
No.

275
00:21:07,640 --> 00:21:09,760
Did you ask?

276
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:13,280
I shouldn't have thought that was
any of my business. Or yours.

277
00:21:19,120 --> 00:21:20,800
Wait here.

278
00:21:23,400 --> 00:21:27,440
Mr Deakin, forgive me for asking,
are these war injuries?

279
00:21:27,440 --> 00:21:29,520
Yes, they are.

280
00:21:29,520 --> 00:21:34,040
Then I'd understand your difficulty
representing somebody
on these sort of charges.

281
00:21:34,040 --> 00:21:36,960
He did speak to me,
not a great deal, but enough,

282
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:40,120
and I can tell you that,
whatever else he might be,

283
00:21:40,120 --> 00:21:43,680
he's not a Nazi sympathiser,
nor is he guilty of treason.

284
00:21:43,680 --> 00:21:48,240
And I'd hope to persuade you
not to assume his guilt

285
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:50,120
or, indeed, to abandon him to hang.

286
00:21:51,160 --> 00:21:53,600
There are a couple of things
I could do to help.

287
00:21:53,600 --> 00:21:56,040
If you'd accept the offer,
I'd be pleased to...

288
00:22:07,520 --> 00:22:09,720
Right, you're going to have to
raise it.

289
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:11,680
All right.

290
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:13,840
How's that?
Yeah. Keep coming. Bit more.

291
00:22:15,160 --> 00:22:16,880
Good?

292
00:22:19,160 --> 00:22:22,280
Hello. What's going on here?
And who are you, darling?

293
00:22:22,280 --> 00:22:25,240
Oh. Well, I'm Sam Stewart.

294
00:22:25,240 --> 00:22:27,760
I don't suppose you live
in one of these big houses?

295
00:22:27,760 --> 00:22:30,000
I do, as a matter of fact.
That one over there.

296
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:33,040
Then this is your lucky day.

297
00:22:33,040 --> 00:22:34,960
We want to knock it down.

298
00:22:38,160 --> 00:22:40,080
Good evening, Miss Stewart.

299
00:22:44,560 --> 00:22:46,480
(RUSHING WATER)

300
00:22:48,200 --> 00:22:50,320
Adam?
I'm up here!

301
00:22:58,360 --> 00:23:00,480
What do you mean, knock us down?
Yes.

302
00:23:00,480 --> 00:23:03,000
Why?
For the access road.

303
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:06,480
Access to what? Shops and houses
they'll be building on The Green.

304
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:09,840
Hastings may need shops and houses,
but why build on The Green?

305
00:23:09,840 --> 00:23:11,920
I thought you'd be pleased.
I am, I think.

306
00:23:11,920 --> 00:23:13,880
I should be delighted, I suppose.

307
00:23:13,880 --> 00:23:16,240
It's exactly what you wanted.

308
00:23:16,240 --> 00:23:18,840
And, of course,
they'll pay you compensation.

309
00:23:18,840 --> 00:23:22,400
There's a meeting at the town hall
tomorrow evening. Not much notice!

310
00:23:22,400 --> 00:23:25,400
Provided they make a good offer,
how much notice do you need?

311
00:23:25,400 --> 00:23:27,680
Oh dear! More problems?
I'm afraid so.

312
00:23:32,120 --> 00:23:34,320
In answer to your question,

313
00:23:34,320 --> 00:23:36,760
I was with Monty
in the Eighth Army.

314
00:23:36,760 --> 00:23:39,760
Tunisia, May 1943,
a place called Medjerda.

315
00:23:41,960 --> 00:23:44,640
I'm sorry to hear it.
I'm not asking for sympathy.

316
00:23:44,640 --> 00:23:47,200
A lot of my friends were killed.

317
00:23:47,200 --> 00:23:49,560
I was invalided home
and went back to the Bar.

318
00:23:49,560 --> 00:23:51,440
Wasn't much else I could do.

319
00:23:53,240 --> 00:23:55,200
(BIRD CRIES)

320
00:24:03,240 --> 00:24:06,200
James won't speak to me.
He won't speak to any of us.

321
00:24:06,200 --> 00:24:08,640
But you've seen him.
I have.

322
00:24:08,640 --> 00:24:10,440
And?

323
00:24:10,440 --> 00:24:12,720
Is there anything
that can give us any hope?

324
00:24:12,720 --> 00:24:14,760
Deakin says you believe
he may be innocent.

325
00:24:14,760 --> 00:24:16,680
That's right.

326
00:24:16,680 --> 00:24:21,440
Do you really think you can find
a way through this? I'm not sure.
I've just seen him the once.

327
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:23,400
It's certainly worth the attempt.

328
00:24:23,400 --> 00:24:25,640
What did he tell you?
Very little.

329
00:24:25,640 --> 00:24:29,800
But it does seem to me
that there's more to the situation
than he's allowing anyone to know.

330
00:24:31,720 --> 00:24:34,560
Jane, I'll talk to Mr Foyle alone,
if you don't mind.

331
00:24:34,560 --> 00:24:36,720
Why don't you show Deakin
round the garden?

332
00:24:36,720 --> 00:24:38,960
Er...yes, of course, dear,
whatever you say.

333
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:41,880
Shall we?

334
00:24:45,520 --> 00:24:49,800
James was never the same after
his mother died. He was only eight.

335
00:24:49,800 --> 00:24:54,000
Maybe that's what this is all about.
She was the only one he confided in.

336
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:57,440
I loved Caroline
more than anyone in the world.

337
00:24:57,440 --> 00:25:00,840
She was everything to me. But James
was more her son than mine,

338
00:25:00,840 --> 00:25:04,720
and after she died
he...drifted away.

339
00:25:05,960 --> 00:25:08,880
Ever any mention of
or sympathy with...

340
00:25:08,880 --> 00:25:11,680
right-wing causes?
No!

341
00:25:11,680 --> 00:25:15,200
A model student at Eton, and at
Sandhurst. A credit to his regiment.

342
00:25:16,160 --> 00:25:19,440
When he was taken prisoner at
Dunkirk, I thought I'd lost him.

343
00:25:20,160 --> 00:25:22,080
Now I almost wish I had.

344
00:25:23,800 --> 00:25:28,640
We're one of the oldest families in
England, and we have a long history
of service to our country:

345
00:25:28,800 --> 00:25:32,760
my father at the Colonial Office,
my grandfather in Salisbury's
administration.

346
00:25:32,760 --> 00:25:34,840
I was an MP for 30 years.

347
00:25:34,840 --> 00:25:38,240
This unit, the British Free Corps -
They're disgusting!

348
00:25:38,240 --> 00:25:40,400
Nothing!

349
00:25:40,400 --> 00:25:44,240
What do you think drove James
to join it?

350
00:25:44,240 --> 00:25:47,080
He was a prisoner of war.
He had been for three years.

351
00:25:48,760 --> 00:25:52,640
He was starving.
They offered him an alternative
to a life behind barbed wire.

352
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:56,400
He didn't know what he was doing.
Wouldn't that be his defence?

353
00:25:56,400 --> 00:25:59,480
Of course it's his defence!
He's not using it.

354
00:25:59,480 --> 00:26:03,080
He's ashamed of himself.
Doesn't appear to be the case.

355
00:26:04,840 --> 00:26:07,040
He's destroying me.

356
00:26:07,040 --> 00:26:11,520
This...house, this land,

357
00:26:11,520 --> 00:26:14,720
my name,
all that I've ever stood for,
he'll bring it all crashing down.

358
00:26:16,920 --> 00:26:20,160
Mr Foyle, you told Deakin
you could help us,

359
00:26:20,160 --> 00:26:22,680
but all you've done so far
is ask a lot of questions.

360
00:26:22,680 --> 00:26:24,640
Why exactly are you here?

361
00:26:34,080 --> 00:26:36,000
Caroline Devereaux...

362
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:39,680
Sometimes I think
she never left this house.

363
00:26:41,320 --> 00:26:43,240
It's as if she never died.

364
00:26:44,480 --> 00:26:46,560
So...er...

365
00:26:46,560 --> 00:26:48,960
how did it happen exactly?

366
00:26:50,040 --> 00:26:52,520
Oh, it was a horrible accident.

367
00:26:53,840 --> 00:26:55,840
She was walking over there.

368
00:26:56,880 --> 00:26:58,800
It was late summer.

369
00:26:59,760 --> 00:27:02,680
The deer can be very dangerous
at that time of year.

370
00:27:02,680 --> 00:27:05,160
Nobody knows
why she got so close to them,

371
00:27:05,160 --> 00:27:07,520
but they gored her
with their antlers.

372
00:27:15,480 --> 00:27:17,680
Ah. Hello.

373
00:27:17,680 --> 00:27:19,920
All right?
I think so.

374
00:27:19,920 --> 00:27:23,320
Do come with us. I was going to show
Mr Deakin the hide. I'd love to.

375
00:27:45,360 --> 00:27:48,480
Come on!
I'm coming!

376
00:27:48,480 --> 00:27:50,400
Slow coach!

377
00:27:58,360 --> 00:28:00,320
It's got a black beak...

378
00:28:00,320 --> 00:28:02,200
and...

379
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:04,280
white patches on its wings.

380
00:28:04,280 --> 00:28:06,760
And what do you think it is?

381
00:28:06,760 --> 00:28:08,880
A...nightingale?

382
00:28:08,880 --> 00:28:10,760
Hm, let me see.

383
00:28:12,960 --> 00:28:15,680
Oh! No, it's a pied flycatcher.

384
00:28:17,280 --> 00:28:19,520
It's come all the way from Africa
to be here.

385
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:22,480
She had it built
especially for James.

386
00:28:23,360 --> 00:28:25,240
Does anyone use it any more?

387
00:28:27,280 --> 00:28:29,560
Well, he wouldn't go near it
after she died.

388
00:28:30,240 --> 00:28:32,160
(BIRD CALLS)

389
00:28:33,720 --> 00:28:35,640
I hope you don't mind me asking...

390
00:28:36,560 --> 00:28:39,000
How well do you get on with him?

391
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:41,920
Well, he was 14
when I married Charles.

392
00:28:42,720 --> 00:28:44,920
He was already at Eton.

393
00:28:44,920 --> 00:28:48,280
But I did what I could.
I tried to be close.

394
00:28:48,280 --> 00:28:52,120
Any sign of any interest in politics,
that sort of thing, at that time?

395
00:28:52,120 --> 00:28:54,320
Not that I know of.

396
00:28:54,320 --> 00:28:57,280
Ah, I think he did want to become
a policeman.

397
00:28:57,280 --> 00:28:59,360
Really?

398
00:28:59,360 --> 00:29:01,560
He was very young.
I don't think he was serious.

399
00:29:02,520 --> 00:29:05,760
So...what other interests
might he have had?

400
00:29:05,760 --> 00:29:08,480
Er...he used to play the piano.
Ah.

401
00:29:08,480 --> 00:29:10,560
He was actually very good.

402
00:29:10,560 --> 00:29:13,280
But there was this business
with his piano teacher.

403
00:29:13,280 --> 00:29:15,400
A man called...er...

404
00:29:15,400 --> 00:29:18,800
Rothmann or Rothstein or something.

405
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:21,160
Anyway...erm...

406
00:29:21,160 --> 00:29:23,680
he left under a bit of a cloud.

407
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:26,000
Mm-hm?
And...er...

408
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:28,240
James lost interest after that
and stopped.

409
00:29:30,240 --> 00:29:33,720
Who else might I talk to
who knew him as a boy?

410
00:29:34,720 --> 00:29:38,760
There was our old housekeeper,
Mrs Ramsay. Mm-hm?

411
00:29:38,760 --> 00:29:42,520
But there's been this terrible
business. What's that?

412
00:29:42,520 --> 00:29:45,560
A young woman was found murdered
in her house.

413
00:29:45,560 --> 00:29:47,920
Murdered?

414
00:29:47,920 --> 00:29:51,720
Oh, I'm sorry,
I thought you'd know all about it.

415
00:29:51,720 --> 00:29:54,040
The police were only here
yesterday.

416
00:29:54,040 --> 00:29:57,680
(SIGHS) My husband's secretary.
She was found strangled.

417
00:30:04,840 --> 00:30:06,960
(KEY TURNS, DOOR CLANGS OPEN)

418
00:30:08,920 --> 00:30:10,800
Dinner, Mr Devereaux.

419
00:30:13,600 --> 00:30:16,400
Are you still not talkative?

420
00:30:16,400 --> 00:30:18,600
Well, let's see
what we've got for you.

421
00:30:18,600 --> 00:30:22,800
Corn-beef hash, beans
and mashed potato.

422
00:30:22,800 --> 00:30:24,440
(WARDER CHUCKLES)

423
00:30:25,760 --> 00:30:27,200
I am sorry.

424
00:30:27,200 --> 00:30:29,640
That was very clumsy of me.

425
00:30:29,640 --> 00:30:31,520
(CHUCKLES)

426
00:30:33,840 --> 00:30:36,400
Nazi scum! Eat it off the floor.

427
00:30:37,640 --> 00:30:41,920
And you'd better get this cell
cleaned up, or I'll have you up
before the governor.

428
00:30:46,080 --> 00:30:48,000
(KEY TURNS IN LOCK)

429
00:31:11,160 --> 00:31:13,360
Not many people here.

430
00:31:13,360 --> 00:31:15,560
Well, they only called the meeting
yesterday.

431
00:31:15,560 --> 00:31:17,360
Don't you think that's a bit
strange?

432
00:31:17,360 --> 00:31:18,960
No. Why?

433
00:31:21,600 --> 00:31:23,880
Good evening, ladies and gentlemen.

434
00:31:23,880 --> 00:31:25,600
Please, take your seats.

435
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:30,440
Let me introduce myself.
I'm Michael Harrison,

436
00:31:30,440 --> 00:31:33,920
working with Harry Clifton here for
the Hastings Planning Committee.

437
00:31:33,920 --> 00:31:36,600
Never heard of it! What good's it
ever done?

438
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:38,000
(LAUGHTER)

439
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:42,160
Ladies and gentlemen, these are the
facts. In the last five years, more
than three million houses

440
00:31:42,160 --> 00:31:44,160
have been damaged or destroyed.

441
00:31:44,160 --> 00:31:48,600
As a country, we now need to build
750,000 new homes,

442
00:31:48,600 --> 00:31:51,240
7,000 of them here in Hastings.

443
00:31:51,240 --> 00:31:55,000
But it may well be that the
Luftwaffe has done us a favour.

444
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:57,120
(JEERING)
We can look on this

445
00:31:57,120 --> 00:32:00,040
not as a challenge, but as an
opportunity.

446
00:32:01,160 --> 00:32:02,920
Highcliffe Green.

447
00:32:04,160 --> 00:32:08,640
It's an empty space, even though
it's only minutes away from the
centre of Hastings.

448
00:32:08,640 --> 00:32:10,720
And here it is again.

449
00:32:11,840 --> 00:32:14,760
The hub of a new development zone,

450
00:32:14,760 --> 00:32:17,960
with purpose-built housing,
improved traffic flow,

451
00:32:17,960 --> 00:32:21,400
the sense and simplicity of
concentric rings.

452
00:32:21,400 --> 00:32:23,640
What's he talking about?
A new modern Hastings,

453
00:32:23,640 --> 00:32:25,560
with a bustling new heart.

454
00:32:25,560 --> 00:32:28,840
But what happens to us? What about
the existing bomb damage?

455
00:32:28,840 --> 00:32:32,000
One at a time, please. May I ask
where you live, sir?

456
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:36,040
Gladwell Avenue. I congratulate you
on your good fortune.

457
00:32:36,040 --> 00:32:40,680
Every resident of Highcliffe Street,
Quay Street and Gladwell Avenue

458
00:32:41,320 --> 00:32:44,080
is going to be required to move...

459
00:32:44,080 --> 00:32:46,320
(UPROAR)
Build it somewhere else!

460
00:32:46,320 --> 00:32:49,640
..but will be generously
compensated.

461
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:51,800
I like the sound of that.

462
00:32:51,800 --> 00:32:54,920
What I'm here to talk to you about,
ladies and gentlemen,

463
00:32:54,920 --> 00:32:57,200
is a new start.

464
00:32:57,200 --> 00:33:01,080
I've looked at these old houses.
Many of them are in a state of
disrepair,

465
00:33:01,080 --> 00:33:03,240
with outmoded plumbing and
electrics.

466
00:33:03,240 --> 00:33:05,720
They're too big and they're
expensive to run.

467
00:33:05,720 --> 00:33:08,560
What I want to say to you is,

468
00:33:08,560 --> 00:33:10,880
welcome to the future.

469
00:33:10,880 --> 00:33:12,760
(APPLAUSE)

470
00:33:13,920 --> 00:33:17,880
Adam Wainwright. I own the guest
house, Hill House, on Highcliffe
Street.

471
00:33:17,880 --> 00:33:22,240
So you're proposing to buy it, knock
it down, and do what exactly?

472
00:33:22,240 --> 00:33:26,640
Well, Hill House stands on what will
be the main thoroughfare to the new
shopping centre.

473
00:33:26,760 --> 00:33:29,720
And you're going to build that on
the green? That's right.

474
00:33:29,720 --> 00:33:32,320
But the green's always been there.

475
00:33:32,320 --> 00:33:36,000
There is no historical significance
to the green. It's just an empty
space.

476
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:38,200
But it's common land.

477
00:33:38,200 --> 00:33:40,960
Exactly. Isn't it common land?
Well, yes, it is.

478
00:33:40,960 --> 00:33:43,560
But I don't think there'd be any
great objections...

479
00:33:43,560 --> 00:33:46,280
(UPROAR)
Isn't it protected, though?

480
00:33:46,280 --> 00:33:49,000
I think you're rather overstating
its importance.

481
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:51,920
People have been grazing their
animals there for centuries.

482
00:33:51,920 --> 00:33:54,720
Let him speak. He's got a point.
How much are you gonna pay us?

483
00:33:54,720 --> 00:33:57,600
(LAUGHTER)
That's the question I'd have asked.

484
00:33:57,600 --> 00:34:00,720
We'll be making valuations in the
weeks to come.

485
00:34:00,720 --> 00:34:03,720
Now you're talking!
Hang on. Are we sure about this?

486
00:34:03,720 --> 00:34:07,640
Why do we need a new development?
Why can't we improve the Hastings
we've already got?

487
00:34:07,640 --> 00:34:11,000
Sit down!
You've had your turn!

488
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:15,720
There will, of course,
be a full and proper consultation
before any works begin.

489
00:34:15,720 --> 00:34:17,640
(MUTTERING)

490
00:34:24,680 --> 00:34:26,920
Adam, are you all right?

491
00:34:26,920 --> 00:34:29,080
You haven't said anything this past
half hour.

492
00:34:29,080 --> 00:34:31,840
I'm sorry, Sam. Miles away.

493
00:34:31,840 --> 00:34:34,280
We should be celebrating,
shouldn't we?

494
00:34:34,280 --> 00:34:38,600
You get the money, you get shot of
Hill House, you can start again.

495
00:34:38,600 --> 00:34:40,720
I wasn't thinking about Hill House.

496
00:34:42,920 --> 00:34:45,120
I really like Hastings.

497
00:34:45,120 --> 00:34:47,000
I know I haven't been here long,
but...

498
00:34:49,480 --> 00:34:52,760
It's just the arrogance of it all
that gets me, Sam.

499
00:34:52,760 --> 00:34:54,800
I mean, look at this green.

500
00:34:54,800 --> 00:34:56,840
It's been here forever.

501
00:34:56,840 --> 00:34:58,880
When William the Conqueror landed,

502
00:34:58,880 --> 00:35:00,920
he probably stood right here.

503
00:35:03,720 --> 00:35:06,600
Isn't this what we've been fighting
for, for the past six years?

504
00:35:08,320 --> 00:35:11,040
England's green and pleasant land.
Exactly.

505
00:35:11,040 --> 00:35:13,760
I think we've earned the right to
run our own lives,

506
00:35:13,760 --> 00:35:17,640
not be pushed around
by some Nazi in a pinstripe suit.

507
00:35:17,640 --> 00:35:20,840
I mean, this is part of the England
we've been defending.

508
00:35:20,840 --> 00:35:25,000
Jerry couldn't invade us.
They couldn't destroy us.

509
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:28,240
So why should we let someone like
Harrison achieve what they didn't?

510
00:35:28,240 --> 00:35:30,440
Are you going to start a resistance
movement?

511
00:35:30,440 --> 00:35:32,080
Yes.

512
00:35:32,080 --> 00:35:34,200
That's exactly what I'm gonna do.

513
00:35:34,200 --> 00:35:38,040
Well then, count me in.

514
00:35:38,040 --> 00:35:41,880
I'll wave the flag
or the machine gun or whatever.

515
00:35:41,880 --> 00:35:43,240
Perfect.

516
00:35:54,640 --> 00:35:56,280
Back again.

517
00:35:59,840 --> 00:36:01,960
I've brought some books.

518
00:36:01,960 --> 00:36:03,920
Decline and Fall.

519
00:36:03,920 --> 00:36:05,840
It seems appropriate.

520
00:36:07,880 --> 00:36:11,000
I like Evelyn Waugh.
So do I.

521
00:36:12,160 --> 00:36:15,160
And it's not too long. I don't think
I should be starting long books.

522
00:36:17,680 --> 00:36:20,920
Thank you. That's very kind of you.
Not at all.

523
00:36:25,600 --> 00:36:29,800
A couple of things have happened
since we last met which may be
of interest to you.

524
00:36:32,320 --> 00:36:34,200
I went to White Friars

525
00:36:34,200 --> 00:36:36,200
and met your father.

526
00:36:37,680 --> 00:36:39,680
Why did you do that?

527
00:36:39,680 --> 00:36:42,200
What's White Friars got to do with
the British Free Corps?

528
00:36:42,200 --> 00:36:44,440
Oh, it helped to know why you joined.

529
00:36:44,440 --> 00:36:46,640
And you think
my father can tell you?

530
00:36:46,640 --> 00:36:48,840
He had an opinion.
I bet he did.

531
00:36:52,760 --> 00:36:55,560
I also learned that you were very
close to your mother.

532
00:36:55,560 --> 00:36:57,880
I wondered what she'd have made of
all this.

533
00:36:57,880 --> 00:37:00,920
Correct me if I'm wrong, but...

534
00:37:00,920 --> 00:37:04,560
goose-stepping your way around
Dresden in an SS uniform

535
00:37:04,560 --> 00:37:07,520
isn't something that I imagine would
have endeared you to her.

536
00:37:11,360 --> 00:37:13,480
I've had enough of this.

537
00:37:13,480 --> 00:37:15,320
I'd like to go back to my cell,
please.

538
00:37:17,880 --> 00:37:19,800
(KEY TURNS IN LOCK)

539
00:37:34,880 --> 00:37:37,360
Sylvie Johnstone?
Yeah, that's me.

540
00:37:37,360 --> 00:37:41,680
I'm Detective Inspector Milner and
this is Detective Constable Perkins.

541
00:37:41,680 --> 00:37:46,000
I believe you know Agnes Lyttleton?
Yes, I know Agnes.

542
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:48,160
Why are you asking?

543
00:37:48,160 --> 00:37:51,640
I'm afraid you're going to have to
prepare yourself for some bad news.
Agnes is dead.

544
00:37:55,760 --> 00:37:57,680
Perkins. Could you?

545
00:37:59,360 --> 00:38:01,680
Dead?
I'm sorry.

546
00:38:02,960 --> 00:38:05,600
What happened?
She was found at home.

547
00:38:05,600 --> 00:38:08,760
She was living with a Mrs Ramsay.
I know. I went there once.

548
00:38:08,760 --> 00:38:11,240
Agnes was very happy there.

549
00:38:11,240 --> 00:38:15,120
It seems that someone came to the
house when she was on her own and
attacked her.

550
00:38:15,120 --> 00:38:17,360
She was killed in the bedroom.

551
00:38:17,360 --> 00:38:19,520
Oh, Lord.

552
00:38:19,520 --> 00:38:23,000
We have to ask you some questions.
But we can come back, if you prefer.

553
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:27,200
I hadn't known her that long.

554
00:38:27,200 --> 00:38:30,120
We met in a pub, got chatting about
horses.

555
00:38:30,120 --> 00:38:32,280
She liked them, too.

556
00:38:33,720 --> 00:38:37,640
I'd moved down from London. I didn't
know anyone. The two of us became
friends.

557
00:38:39,440 --> 00:38:41,520
Is she really dead?

558
00:38:41,520 --> 00:38:43,360
I'm afraid so.

559
00:38:44,360 --> 00:38:46,480
I wonder if Jack knows?

560
00:38:46,480 --> 00:38:47,840
Jack?

561
00:38:47,840 --> 00:38:49,640
Who's Jack?

562
00:38:49,640 --> 00:38:52,480
Her young man.
She never told me his surname.

563
00:38:52,480 --> 00:38:54,400
Jack.

564
00:38:54,400 --> 00:38:56,680
She was crazy about him.

565
00:38:56,680 --> 00:38:59,120
Photo by the bed,
all that sort of thing.

566
00:38:59,120 --> 00:39:01,560
Did you ever see the photograph?
No.

567
00:39:02,720 --> 00:39:04,840
Look, shall I go and tie this up?

568
00:39:08,760 --> 00:39:10,680
Um...

569
00:39:10,680 --> 00:39:12,760
What else can you tell me about Jack?

570
00:39:13,760 --> 00:39:15,760
Not very much.

571
00:39:15,760 --> 00:39:18,360
She was very secretive about him cos
he was...

572
00:39:18,360 --> 00:39:21,440
You know, he was doing something
hush-hush overseas.

573
00:39:21,440 --> 00:39:24,480
Do you know where? Was it France?
No, in Germany.

574
00:39:24,480 --> 00:39:28,520
She shouldn't have told me that,
but she mentioned it once.
I couldn't believe it.

575
00:39:28,520 --> 00:39:30,960
Jack had a friend. He was coming to
see her.

576
00:39:30,960 --> 00:39:33,160
What friend?
She didn't say.

577
00:39:33,160 --> 00:39:36,160
She just said she'd heard from
someone who had news about Jack.

578
00:39:36,160 --> 00:39:38,360
Of course, she was sick with worry
about him.

579
00:39:38,360 --> 00:39:41,560
But he had news for her
and he was coming down to Brighton
and he'd see her.

580
00:39:41,560 --> 00:39:43,520
That was about a week ago.

581
00:39:43,520 --> 00:39:47,040
And she didn't give you the name of
this friend? She never said, no.

582
00:39:47,040 --> 00:39:49,560
So, what's she called, then?

583
00:39:49,560 --> 00:39:51,080
Who?
The horse.

584
00:39:52,200 --> 00:39:55,680
It's not a mare. It's a stallion.
Can't you tell?

585
00:40:17,600 --> 00:40:21,320
We fought them on the beaches.
We fought them on the fields
and on the hills.

586
00:40:21,320 --> 00:40:23,440
We fought them on the streets.

587
00:40:23,440 --> 00:40:26,720
But what was the point if we were
going to sell those beaches,

588
00:40:26,720 --> 00:40:29,520
those hills and those fields and
those streets?

589
00:40:32,640 --> 00:40:35,520
Here would be interesting.
Good sense of place.

590
00:40:39,520 --> 00:40:41,880
'We fought them on the streets.'

591
00:40:41,880 --> 00:40:46,280
But what was the point if we were
going to sell those beaches, those
hills and those fields and streets

592
00:40:46,720 --> 00:40:49,200
for the sake of flats and shops we
don't even need?

593
00:40:53,280 --> 00:40:56,000
I can't talk about the family,
Mr Foyle.

594
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:00,400
I was with them for many years.
Anything I might have seen, well...

595
00:41:00,400 --> 00:41:03,160
You know, it wasn't my place
to see anything.

596
00:41:03,160 --> 00:41:06,080
I do understand your discretion,
of course.

597
00:41:06,080 --> 00:41:09,360
But we must remember that tomorrow
this boy could be sentenced to hang.

598
00:41:09,360 --> 00:41:12,440
It's a terrible thing, him going
over to the Germans like that.

599
00:41:12,440 --> 00:41:14,560
Was it a surprise?

600
00:41:14,560 --> 00:41:17,360
Of course it was.
He was never like that.

601
00:41:17,360 --> 00:41:21,640
Well, obviously, he was never the
same after the death of his mother.

602
00:41:21,640 --> 00:41:23,360
He adored her. We all did.

603
00:41:25,760 --> 00:41:27,880
A happy family, would you say?

604
00:41:27,880 --> 00:41:31,240
They were a family like any other,
Mr Foyle. They had their ups and
downs.

605
00:41:32,640 --> 00:41:35,640
What can you tell me about the piano
teacher?

606
00:41:35,640 --> 00:41:38,360
Oh, yes,
that was a bad business, too.

607
00:41:38,360 --> 00:41:41,040
His name was Rothstein.

608
00:41:41,040 --> 00:41:43,240
Simon Rothstein.

609
00:41:43,240 --> 00:41:47,440
He was a Hebrew. He was a good man.
That's what I thought.

610
00:41:47,440 --> 00:41:51,640
He stole some of Lady Devereaux's
jewellery and went to prison.

611
00:41:51,640 --> 00:41:55,240
That was just a few weeks before her
own accident.

612
00:41:55,240 --> 00:41:57,440
You see what I'm saying?

613
00:41:57,440 --> 00:42:00,120
James lost the two people who were
closest to him.

614
00:42:00,120 --> 00:42:02,120
Maybe that's what turned his head.

615
00:42:05,560 --> 00:42:06,960
Thank you.

616
00:42:07,920 --> 00:42:11,600
Sir Charles' secretary was staying
here, isn't that right?

617
00:42:11,600 --> 00:42:13,920
Agnes Lyttleton.
You heard about that? Mmm.

618
00:42:15,160 --> 00:42:19,520
I'm not sure I can live here now.
The house isn't the same any more.

619
00:42:19,520 --> 00:42:21,400
I'd understand that.

620
00:42:21,400 --> 00:42:24,080
You don't suppose...

621
00:42:24,080 --> 00:42:27,120
It couldn't have had anything to do
with Master James, could it?

622
00:42:27,120 --> 00:42:28,840
Of course it's possible.

623
00:42:28,840 --> 00:42:31,600
Because I have something that might
help you.

624
00:42:31,600 --> 00:42:33,760
I er...

625
00:42:33,760 --> 00:42:37,160
I found it when I was going through
her laundry. It fell out of a
pocket.

626
00:42:43,080 --> 00:42:47,360
Now, that is from her young man.
He was a prisoner-of-war in Germany.

627
00:42:47,360 --> 00:42:49,200
And he wrote regularly.

628
00:42:50,720 --> 00:42:53,160
And this is addressed to a hotel in
London.

629
00:42:53,160 --> 00:42:55,840
And that's her handwriting on the
envelope.

630
00:42:58,120 --> 00:43:01,880
So she might have been forwarding it,
perhaps? So it would seem.

631
00:43:01,880 --> 00:43:04,280
Did she ever mention this
Mr Armstrong?

632
00:43:04,280 --> 00:43:08,160
No. And as far as I know, she never
visited London, not while she was
with me.

633
00:43:08,160 --> 00:43:11,720
I was going to pass it on
to the detective who was here.

634
00:43:11,720 --> 00:43:14,760
Well, I could do that for you.
What's his name?

635
00:43:25,720 --> 00:43:29,560
My name's Jack Stanford. Thank you
for agreeing to see me.

636
00:43:29,560 --> 00:43:31,760
You're a friend of James Devereaux?

637
00:43:31,760 --> 00:43:33,920
Yes. You're representing him,
is that right?

638
00:43:33,920 --> 00:43:35,800
I would do, if he let me.

639
00:43:37,200 --> 00:43:38,680
Thank you.

640
00:43:40,840 --> 00:43:45,400
James and I were POWs together.

641
00:43:45,400 --> 00:43:48,440
Where?
Oflag 79. In Brunswick.

642
00:43:49,640 --> 00:43:52,600
That would have been before '43.
I knew him later as well.

643
00:43:54,160 --> 00:43:57,720
The British Free Corps? I'm afraid
you're going to have to forgive me.

644
00:43:57,720 --> 00:43:59,920
I can't fully explain myself.

645
00:43:59,920 --> 00:44:03,360
Indeed, I must ask you
not to mention to anyone
that you've met me.

646
00:44:03,360 --> 00:44:05,240
It's a matter of national security.

647
00:44:06,720 --> 00:44:09,280
How can I help you?
Has he said anything?

648
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:13,360
I mean, he's on trial for his life.
Has he put forward any defence?

649
00:44:13,360 --> 00:44:15,440
Not at all. He refuses to speak.

650
00:44:15,440 --> 00:44:16,680
Why?

651
00:44:17,840 --> 00:44:19,720
Well, maybe you could tell me.

652
00:44:22,560 --> 00:44:25,200
I knew James very well, for a time.

653
00:44:25,200 --> 00:44:27,240
I never completely understood him.

654
00:44:27,240 --> 00:44:29,400
Actually, I thought he was dead.

655
00:44:29,400 --> 00:44:32,480
I couldn't believe it when he turned
up after Dresden.

656
00:44:32,480 --> 00:44:35,040
Maybe, in a way, it would be better
if he had died.

657
00:44:36,360 --> 00:44:38,040
Maybe it would.

658
00:44:39,120 --> 00:44:41,360
When does the trial begin?

659
00:44:42,560 --> 00:44:47,120
Tomorrow. The trial's a formality.
He's pleading guilty.

660
00:44:48,680 --> 00:44:51,240
Oh, well,
then there's nothing I can do.

661
00:45:03,440 --> 00:45:06,320
This is from Jack.
Do you know who that is?

662
00:45:06,320 --> 00:45:09,680
Jack was Agnes Lyttleton's young
man.

663
00:45:09,680 --> 00:45:13,440
And I presume the man in the
photograph that had been taken from
her room.

664
00:45:13,440 --> 00:45:15,440
He was a prisoner of war.

665
00:45:15,440 --> 00:45:17,440
It was written in February.

666
00:45:17,440 --> 00:45:20,400
It took almost six months to arrive.

667
00:45:20,400 --> 00:45:23,080
Well, not surprising, given the state
of things in Europe.

668
00:45:23,080 --> 00:45:25,640
It doesn't give much away.

669
00:45:25,640 --> 00:45:28,600
Which, I suppose, is what you expect
with German censorship.

670
00:45:28,600 --> 00:45:31,000
He wonders when the war will end.

671
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:34,320
I imagine there were thousands of
letters like this written every day.

672
00:45:34,320 --> 00:45:36,920
This thing about the weather.

673
00:45:36,920 --> 00:45:40,040
"It's raining dogs and cats." Do we
normally say it like that?

674
00:45:40,040 --> 00:45:43,080
No, it should be "cats and dogs".
He's got it the wrong way round.

675
00:45:43,080 --> 00:45:46,000
Unless he's trying to tell us
something.

676
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:49,520
And the date?
Is that unusual or am I imagining it?

677
00:45:49,520 --> 00:45:52,240
We'd normally write it...
The other way round.

678
00:45:52,240 --> 00:45:54,480
10th February, 1945.

679
00:45:57,520 --> 00:46:00,080
Sir, I appreciate you bringing this
to my attention.

680
00:46:01,080 --> 00:46:05,440
I thought I'd take a look at the
hotel this is addressed to. Mind if
I hang onto this?

681
00:46:05,440 --> 00:46:07,640
Of course not.
Thank you.

682
00:46:07,640 --> 00:46:10,520
And if there's anything else I can
do to help...

683
00:46:10,520 --> 00:46:14,400
There is. Simon Rothstein, piano
teacher to the Devereaux.

684
00:46:14,400 --> 00:46:17,880
Arrested for theft a long while ago,
but anything you can turn up
would help.

685
00:46:17,880 --> 00:46:19,800
I'll check the files.

686
00:46:26,400 --> 00:46:28,600
So, what did he want?

687
00:46:28,600 --> 00:46:33,120
You searched the house and the room,
Agnes's room. Yes.

688
00:46:33,120 --> 00:46:36,320
So, why didn't you find the letter?
Which letter?

689
00:46:36,320 --> 00:46:39,200
The letter from Jack,
Agnes' young man.

690
00:46:39,200 --> 00:46:41,880
I never saw any letter.
Exactly, constable.

691
00:46:41,880 --> 00:46:45,760
But if you'd been doing your job
properly, you'd have found it.

692
00:46:45,760 --> 00:46:50,040
So, has he got it? If you mean
DCS Foyle, yes, he's got it.

693
00:46:50,040 --> 00:46:52,240
And he's going to keep it
a while longer.

694
00:46:52,240 --> 00:46:54,680
Mr Foyle is helping us with our
enquiries.

695
00:46:54,680 --> 00:46:57,120
I thought he'd left the police.

696
00:46:58,560 --> 00:47:00,240
Constable...

697
00:47:00,240 --> 00:47:03,160
if you and I are going to work
together,

698
00:47:03,160 --> 00:47:06,160
do you think you could try showing
just a modicum of respect?

699
00:47:06,160 --> 00:47:08,120
Of course, sir.

700
00:47:08,120 --> 00:47:10,800
For you or for him?

701
00:47:13,240 --> 00:47:17,840
We've got the mains drainage coming
down this right flank to that point
and then cutting in.

702
00:47:18,160 --> 00:47:21,200
You're a bit premature, aren't you?

703
00:47:21,200 --> 00:47:23,080
I'm sorry?
Do you remember me?

704
00:47:23,080 --> 00:47:26,160
No. We met at the town hall
the other evening.

705
00:47:26,160 --> 00:47:30,680
Because I opposed your sordid little
scheme, I don't suppose you took a
blind bit of notice?

706
00:47:30,680 --> 00:47:33,440
Keep your hair on. Yeah, I remember
you, you're...

707
00:47:33,440 --> 00:47:35,560
Adam Wainwright.
Gladwell Avenue.

708
00:47:35,560 --> 00:47:37,560
Hill House, Highcliffe Street.

709
00:47:37,560 --> 00:47:40,800
I'm sorry, Mr Wainwright, but the
meeting's over and I'm busy.

710
00:47:40,800 --> 00:47:43,160
Do you know what I despise about
you, Mr Harrison?

711
00:47:43,160 --> 00:47:47,600
It's not that you're changing
Hastings, not that you have a vision
for the future.

712
00:47:47,600 --> 00:47:50,600
No, what I detest about you
is your high-handed attitude,

713
00:47:50,600 --> 00:47:53,400
this unshakeable belief that you
really know what's best.

714
00:47:53,400 --> 00:47:56,280
We are consulting...
You don't care about this area,

715
00:47:56,280 --> 00:47:59,920
that this piece of land has history
or what it means to the people who
live here.

716
00:47:59,920 --> 00:48:02,560
It's all just money to you.
Eric, ask this man to move on.

717
00:48:02,560 --> 00:48:05,320
No, I will not move on. I live here.

718
00:48:05,320 --> 00:48:08,200
Why don't you move on? Take your
equipment with you!

719
00:48:08,200 --> 00:48:10,520
I'll have the law onto you! That's
council property.

720
00:48:10,520 --> 00:48:12,520
Is this council property?

721
00:48:12,520 --> 00:48:14,920
Someone call a policeman!

722
00:48:14,920 --> 00:48:17,280
That's enough! Stop that!
Get off!

723
00:48:18,520 --> 00:48:20,000
Get off me!

724
00:48:23,520 --> 00:48:25,440
What have you done?

725
00:48:53,000 --> 00:48:57,000
Mr Foyle! What are you doing here?
Sam told me what happened.

726
00:48:57,000 --> 00:48:59,120
Am I in a lot of trouble?

727
00:48:59,120 --> 00:49:01,160
The man, is he...?

728
00:49:01,160 --> 00:49:03,400
Oh, he's all right, as it turns out.

729
00:49:03,400 --> 00:49:07,560
But assaulting a planning committee
member is perhaps not the wisest
thing to be doing.

730
00:49:07,560 --> 00:49:09,600
Are they going to press charges?

731
00:49:09,600 --> 00:49:13,360
No, I persuaded Mr Harrison that a
court case might not be in his best
interests.

732
00:49:13,360 --> 00:49:15,200
So I can go?
You can.

733
00:49:15,200 --> 00:49:16,480
Thank you.

734
00:49:17,560 --> 00:49:20,120
How am I going to face Sam?
Good question.

735
00:49:20,120 --> 00:49:22,280
Do you think she'll forgive me?

736
00:49:22,280 --> 00:49:25,000
I don't think you've got too much to
worry about.

737
00:49:25,840 --> 00:49:27,720
(BELL TOLLS)

738
00:49:36,440 --> 00:49:38,440
Mr Devereaux.

739
00:49:38,440 --> 00:49:42,080
You remember your KC, Mr Carstairs.
Yes, of course.

740
00:49:42,080 --> 00:49:46,400
Mr Devereaux, let me implore you for
one last time.

741
00:49:48,040 --> 00:49:50,440
When we go upstairs, you will be
tried for high treason

742
00:49:50,440 --> 00:49:52,640
under the Treachery Act of 1940,

743
00:49:52,640 --> 00:49:57,160
as opposed to offences against the
Defence Regulations of the year
before.

744
00:49:57,280 --> 00:49:59,920
There is one critical difference
between them.

745
00:49:59,920 --> 00:50:03,400
If you're found guilty, there can be
no leeway.

746
00:50:03,400 --> 00:50:07,280
The judge can show you no clemency,
do you understand that?

747
00:50:08,440 --> 00:50:10,560
How long will it take?

748
00:50:10,560 --> 00:50:13,160
If you insist on offering no defence,

749
00:50:13,160 --> 00:50:15,880
if you intend to plead guilty,

750
00:50:15,880 --> 00:50:18,000
then the whole thing
may be over very quickly.

751
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:21,080
The judge will sentence you and that
will be that.

752
00:50:21,080 --> 00:50:23,160
No witnesses?

753
00:50:23,160 --> 00:50:25,320
Not unless you enter a defence.

754
00:50:25,320 --> 00:50:27,160
Is my father there?

755
00:50:28,440 --> 00:50:30,200
I believe he's in the public
gallery.

756
00:50:32,960 --> 00:50:35,800
Well, thanks for your time,
Mr Deakin, Mr Carstairs.

757
00:50:35,800 --> 00:50:37,800
I just want it to be over with.

758
00:50:48,600 --> 00:50:50,800
I think it's absolutely splendid.

759
00:50:50,800 --> 00:50:53,240
I didn't know you had it in you.
Didn't you?

760
00:50:53,240 --> 00:50:56,440
You're quite right to show them
they're not going to get away
with it.

761
00:50:56,440 --> 00:51:00,480
Don't you agree, sir? There might be
more productive routes.

762
00:51:00,480 --> 00:51:03,240
I must go. The trouble is,
everybody's taken the money.

763
00:51:03,240 --> 00:51:05,280
Because they don't care about the
green.

764
00:51:05,280 --> 00:51:07,880
To them, it's just a patch of grass.
Thank you, Mr West.

765
00:51:07,880 --> 00:51:10,200
Which green are you talking about?
Our green.

766
00:51:10,200 --> 00:51:12,200
This one?
Yes, the very same.

767
00:51:12,200 --> 00:51:15,040
Well, that's not just any old green.
Isn't it?

768
00:51:15,040 --> 00:51:19,280
No, it's not. They were going
to excavate that not so very many
years ago.

769
00:51:19,280 --> 00:51:21,320
Some settlement site or another.

770
00:51:21,320 --> 00:51:23,480
Settlement? How do you know about
that?

771
00:51:23,480 --> 00:51:26,840
School used to dig up all sorts of
stuff there, pottery, that sort of
thing.

772
00:51:26,840 --> 00:51:30,480
Where is it now? No idea.
Could very well still be there.

773
00:51:30,480 --> 00:51:33,400
Where?
The school. St Saviour's.

774
00:51:33,400 --> 00:51:35,640
Thank you.
Not at all. Bye.

775
00:51:35,640 --> 00:51:37,720
St Saviour's.

776
00:51:37,720 --> 00:51:39,680
How appropriate.

777
00:51:59,160 --> 00:52:00,720
All rise.

778
00:52:12,600 --> 00:52:15,320
Detective Chief Superintendent
Foyle.

779
00:52:15,320 --> 00:52:19,080
We met in court rather more times
than either of us might care to
remember.

780
00:52:19,080 --> 00:52:21,720
Now, what is it that brings you here
today?

781
00:52:21,720 --> 00:52:26,160
Well, I hope you can tell me what you
remember about an old case that needs
clearing up.

782
00:52:26,160 --> 00:52:28,360
A man called Rothstein, a piano
teacher.

783
00:52:28,360 --> 00:52:30,800
Piano teacher?
Simon Rothstein.

784
00:52:30,800 --> 00:52:33,080
Piano teacher to the Devereaux.

785
00:52:33,080 --> 00:52:34,880
Oh, yes.

786
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:36,520
Rothstein.

787
00:52:36,520 --> 00:52:39,480
I remember now - petty theft.

788
00:52:39,480 --> 00:52:42,080
What exactly is your interest
in the case?

789
00:52:42,080 --> 00:52:45,880
Not so much in the case
as the sentence you handed down.

790
00:52:45,880 --> 00:52:48,200
Five years.
With hard labour.

791
00:52:48,200 --> 00:52:51,000
Which led to his death in prison.

792
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:54,560
Yes, well, I can't comment
on past cases.

793
00:52:54,560 --> 00:52:58,600
It seems the jewellery he was
supposed to have stolen was worth
only about 50.

794
00:52:58,600 --> 00:53:00,520
Theft is still theft, Foyle.

795
00:53:00,520 --> 00:53:03,080
I thought you, of all people, would
appreciate that.

796
00:53:03,080 --> 00:53:07,480
Of course. But even so, five years'
hard labour for a first offence seems
unnecessarily harsh.

797
00:53:07,880 --> 00:53:10,080
It was a grave breach of trust.

798
00:53:10,080 --> 00:53:13,120
Here you have a man, a refugee,

799
00:53:13,120 --> 00:53:18,440
welcomed into this country and into
the home of one of our most ancient
and distinguished families...

800
00:53:18,560 --> 00:53:21,080
How many cases would you say you'd
tried over the years?

801
00:53:21,080 --> 00:53:22,720
Thousands.

802
00:53:22,720 --> 00:53:25,600
Do you remember them all in such
detail or is it just this one?

803
00:53:25,600 --> 00:53:27,920
I'm not quite sure I like your tone.

804
00:53:27,920 --> 00:53:31,720
No, I was simply wondering what makes
this one so memorable for you?

805
00:53:31,720 --> 00:53:34,840
I've already told you. I greatly
admired Sir Charles Devereaux.

806
00:53:34,840 --> 00:53:36,800
He was an outstanding MP.

807
00:53:36,800 --> 00:53:38,920
Do you know him?

808
00:53:38,920 --> 00:53:41,040
We may have met.

809
00:53:41,040 --> 00:53:43,960
But I had absolutely no reason not
to try that case.

810
00:53:43,960 --> 00:53:46,080
The evidence was indisputable.

811
00:53:46,080 --> 00:53:48,040
Charles didn't even appear
as a witness.

812
00:53:48,040 --> 00:53:49,400
Charles?

813
00:53:49,400 --> 00:53:51,840
That would be Sir Charles?

814
00:53:51,840 --> 00:53:55,920
It would help, don't you think,
to discount the possibility that...

815
00:53:55,920 --> 00:54:00,880
Charles, in any way, influenced this
hugely disproportionate sentence?

816
00:54:00,880 --> 00:54:03,440
I think you should leave now.

817
00:54:04,360 --> 00:54:06,000
I'll see myself out.

818
00:54:07,720 --> 00:54:09,640
JUDGE: 'James Devereaux,

819
00:54:09,640 --> 00:54:13,960
I have read the depositions and the
exhibits in this case.

820
00:54:13,960 --> 00:54:17,520
I am satisfied you knew what you did.

821
00:54:17,520 --> 00:54:21,520
And you did it intentionally and
deliberately,

822
00:54:21,520 --> 00:54:26,240
in the knowledge that
becoming a member of the so-called
British Free Corps

823
00:54:27,320 --> 00:54:29,760
amounted to high treason.'

824
00:54:33,360 --> 00:54:37,120
But it was a lie. It was all lies.

825
00:54:38,160 --> 00:54:41,280
He stole nothing. Wasn't there
something about a necklace?

826
00:54:41,280 --> 00:54:43,480
You think he would steal
from Lady Devereaux?

827
00:54:44,280 --> 00:54:46,480
He respected her.

828
00:54:46,480 --> 00:54:49,520
He would do anything for her,
and for her son, also.

829
00:54:51,640 --> 00:54:54,520
Rothstein, you must help me!
Run, Lady Devereaux, run!

830
00:54:54,520 --> 00:54:57,560
..this warrior from England.
Die!

831
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:00,960
What's going on here?

832
00:55:08,800 --> 00:55:11,480
JUDGE: 'James Devereaux,

833
00:55:11,480 --> 00:55:14,520
you come from a noble family,

834
00:55:14,520 --> 00:55:18,280
one that has long given service
to the nation.

835
00:55:18,280 --> 00:55:22,240
But that only casts your
transgressions in a harsher light.

836
00:55:22,240 --> 00:55:26,880
You now stand a self-confessed
traitor to your king and country.

837
00:55:28,080 --> 00:55:31,280
And you have forfeited
your right to live.

838
00:55:32,560 --> 00:55:34,840
'But that was the mistake he made,
you see.'

839
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:37,920
He got too close to her.

840
00:55:38,920 --> 00:55:42,480
'My son knew too many secrets,
Mr Foyle.'

841
00:55:43,360 --> 00:55:45,560
That is why he had to be
got out of there.

842
00:55:45,560 --> 00:55:47,920
That is why he had
to be locked away.

843
00:55:53,600 --> 00:55:56,920
The sentence from this court is that
you be taken from here

844
00:55:56,920 --> 00:55:59,840
to a place of lawful execution

845
00:55:59,840 --> 00:56:04,400
and hanged from the neck until you
are dead.

846
00:56:04,400 --> 00:56:07,400
The Lord have mercy on your soul.

847
00:56:07,400 --> 00:56:08,640
Amen.

848
00:56:17,200 --> 00:56:18,960
Take him down.

849
00:56:22,840 --> 00:56:25,960
(JOURNALISTS SHOUT QUESTIONS)
Sir Charles! Sir Charles!

850
00:56:28,040 --> 00:56:30,160
Will there be an appeal?

851
00:56:33,240 --> 00:56:35,360
What have you to say to the press?

852
00:56:35,360 --> 00:56:37,160
Thank you, Mr Carstairs.

853
00:56:37,160 --> 00:56:39,840
I wish I could have done something
more to help.

854
00:56:39,840 --> 00:56:42,600
I can't help feeling there's
something more to all this.

855
00:56:42,600 --> 00:56:44,480
I'm so sorry.

856
00:57:00,160 --> 00:57:03,680
"In his summing-up, the judge said
that he had no alternative

857
00:57:03,680 --> 00:57:06,200
but to pass
the gravest sentence of all.

858
00:57:06,200 --> 00:57:09,520
James Devereaux had been able to
offer no defence

859
00:57:09,520 --> 00:57:12,760
and will now be returned to his cell
to await the hangman."

860
00:57:14,720 --> 00:57:16,840
Afternoon.
Can I help you?

861
00:57:16,840 --> 00:57:21,560
I hope so. Do you have a George
Armstrong staying or working here?

862
00:57:21,560 --> 00:57:23,400
Never heard of him.

863
00:57:23,400 --> 00:57:25,280
Got a letter for him.

864
00:57:26,320 --> 00:57:28,480
No, there's no George Armstrong
here.

865
00:57:28,480 --> 00:57:30,960
Who are you?
The name's Foyle.

866
00:57:32,400 --> 00:57:34,600
I can't help you, I'm afraid.

867
00:57:34,600 --> 00:57:38,200
Right. You've never received anything
like this before? No.

868
00:57:38,200 --> 00:57:41,400
And you're not used as a mail box or
a forwarding address?

869
00:57:41,400 --> 00:57:44,760
We're a hotel, Mr Foyle, that's all.
You can see for yourself.

870
00:57:44,760 --> 00:57:46,800
Thank you very much.

871
00:57:48,840 --> 00:57:50,680
I can take that for you,
if you like.

872
00:57:50,680 --> 00:57:53,000
Why would you wanna do that, Mr...?

873
00:57:53,000 --> 00:57:57,320
Dillon. It's got our address on it.
If someone comes in,
I can hand it over.

874
00:57:57,320 --> 00:58:00,240
Better still, if anyone comes in,
send them to me. I'll hand it over.

875
00:58:18,280 --> 00:58:21,200
This is Dillon. There's something
you need to know.

876
00:58:28,360 --> 00:58:30,600
What's this?
It's a radius.

877
00:58:30,600 --> 00:58:32,800
A radius of what?

878
00:58:32,800 --> 00:58:35,600
A radius is a bone in the forearm,
my dear.

879
00:58:35,600 --> 00:58:38,520
What else did you find,
Miss Longbridge? Oh.

880
00:58:38,520 --> 00:58:40,680
Coins and pottery.

881
00:58:40,680 --> 00:58:44,440
And we've found some lanterns. Some
of them are in very good condition.

882
00:58:44,440 --> 00:58:45,920
And this.

883
00:58:53,960 --> 00:58:55,880
It's very old.

884
00:58:57,600 --> 00:59:00,320
But I've never been able
to discover what it's for.

885
00:59:02,640 --> 00:59:05,320
I don't suppose we can borrow this?
I don't think so.

886
00:59:05,320 --> 00:59:08,480
We'll take very great care of it.
I suppose so.

887
00:59:08,480 --> 00:59:10,320
Thank you. Thank you very much.

888
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:14,720
I don't suppose you remember a pupil
called Christopher Foyle?

889
00:59:16,520 --> 00:59:18,600
Christopher Foyle?

890
00:59:18,600 --> 00:59:22,440
Yes, Christopher Foyle.

891
00:59:22,440 --> 00:59:25,720
I remember him. Always asking
questions.

892
00:59:25,720 --> 00:59:28,200
I often wondered
what happened to him.

893
00:59:34,640 --> 00:59:36,520
Oh, I'm sorry.

894
00:59:37,480 --> 00:59:40,640
There were Romans in Hastings.
Somebody must have written about it.

895
00:59:40,640 --> 00:59:42,200
Goodbye!

896
00:59:44,520 --> 00:59:47,240
So, where do we start?
Well, there's the museum.

897
00:59:47,240 --> 00:59:50,000
Or back to the library.
There's that college in Brighton.

898
00:59:51,560 --> 00:59:53,000
(LAUGHS)

899
00:59:55,120 --> 00:59:57,160
Well, I know where I'm going to
start.

900
00:59:57,160 --> 00:59:58,800
The kitchen.

901
00:59:58,800 --> 01:00:00,240
Tea.

902
01:00:08,680 --> 01:00:10,680
Well, it went exactly as I said.

903
01:00:10,680 --> 01:00:12,880
Sentenced to hang.

904
01:00:12,880 --> 01:00:14,800
When is that likely to happen?
The 17th.

905
01:00:15,880 --> 01:00:18,520
Devilish quick. I suppose they want
to get it over with.

906
01:00:20,240 --> 01:00:22,640
So, when are you leaving for
America?

907
01:00:22,640 --> 01:00:24,400
The same day.

908
01:00:24,400 --> 01:00:27,520
Well, you did everything you could.

909
01:00:29,880 --> 01:00:31,880
I wonder.
Look here, Mr Foyle.

910
01:00:33,120 --> 01:00:35,120
Why don't you come clean with me?

911
01:00:36,320 --> 01:00:40,200
I've made some enquiries about you
and, frankly, you've misled me.

912
01:00:40,200 --> 01:00:42,960
You're not even a policeman,
not any more.

913
01:00:42,960 --> 01:00:45,800
What is your interest
in James Devereaux?

914
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:51,640
Well, in the circumstances, whatever
interest I may or may not have in him
is irrelevant.

915
01:00:51,960 --> 01:00:56,280
In the interests of justice, my
concern is as great as I'd expect
yours to be.

916
01:00:56,280 --> 01:01:01,360
The sentence has been passed in a
court of law. It's over.

917
01:01:01,360 --> 01:01:03,600
There's nothing you can do,
Mr Foyle.

918
01:01:03,600 --> 01:01:06,680
I disagree. It's obviously of no
interest to you.

919
01:01:06,680 --> 01:01:10,680
But it is to me why Sir Charles'
secretary was murdered at the time
all this was happening.

920
01:01:10,680 --> 01:01:13,200
I'd certainly like to know
where Jack is,

921
01:01:13,200 --> 01:01:15,640
the prisoner-of-war who was writing
to her,

922
01:01:15,640 --> 01:01:20,080
and why the Devereaux's piano teacher
was the victim of a miscarriage of
justice and died in prison.

923
01:01:20,320 --> 01:01:22,360
So it seems to me
there's a lot to be done.

924
01:01:22,360 --> 01:01:25,760
Since clearly no-one else is gonna do
it, I will. Excuse me.

925
01:01:27,640 --> 01:01:28,960
Jack?

926
01:01:30,640 --> 01:01:32,360
Er...

927
01:01:32,360 --> 01:01:35,880
I had a young man in the office
named Jack a couple of days ago.

928
01:01:35,880 --> 01:01:39,240
He introduced himself
as a friend of James Devereaux.

929
01:01:39,240 --> 01:01:41,160
They were POWs together in Germany.

930
01:01:41,160 --> 01:01:42,840
And?

931
01:01:43,680 --> 01:01:45,600
He was very mysterious.

932
01:01:46,920 --> 01:01:49,040
Perhaps I shouldn't be telling you
this.

933
01:01:50,800 --> 01:01:53,000
He wanted to help James.

934
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:56,520
But, at the same time, he wasn't
giving anything away.

935
01:01:58,400 --> 01:02:00,520
I also saw him in court.

936
01:02:00,520 --> 01:02:01,840
Surname?

937
01:02:03,040 --> 01:02:04,960
Stanford.

938
01:02:08,360 --> 01:02:09,800
Thank you.

939
01:02:14,280 --> 01:02:16,160
Mr Foyle?

940
01:02:16,160 --> 01:02:19,080
Yes. I wonder if you could
come with me, sir?

941
01:02:20,760 --> 01:02:22,680
Yes, all right.

942
01:02:33,480 --> 01:02:35,840
Mr Foyle for you, sir.
Ah.

943
01:02:35,840 --> 01:02:38,160
Mr Foyle.

944
01:02:38,160 --> 01:02:41,920
I suppose we ought to apologise
to you, for bringing you here
in this way.

945
01:02:41,920 --> 01:02:44,800
No, not at all, always a pleasure.
Thank you, Walcott.

946
01:02:44,800 --> 01:02:48,120
I expect you're wondering what this
is all about?

947
01:02:48,120 --> 01:02:53,040
Well, intelligence services
communicating with prisoners
overseas, perhaps?

948
01:02:54,880 --> 01:02:57,640
You have a letter of ours.
I wonder if I could have it?

949
01:02:57,640 --> 01:02:58,640
Ah.

950
01:02:59,800 --> 01:03:02,560
Forgive me. You are?
My name is Brenner.

951
01:03:02,560 --> 01:03:04,720
And this is Jack Stanford.

952
01:03:04,720 --> 01:03:08,760
He was with James Devereaux
in Oflag 79 and then in Dresden.

953
01:03:08,760 --> 01:03:10,400
How do you do?

954
01:03:10,400 --> 01:03:12,200
How do you do?

955
01:03:13,160 --> 01:03:16,000
This is not actually
addressed to you.

956
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:20,400
Even so, it was intended for my
office, Mr Foyle, and it is quite
important.

957
01:03:21,640 --> 01:03:25,440
It's important to the police, since
it turned up as part of a murder
investigation.

958
01:03:25,440 --> 01:03:27,760
So any light you could shed on that
would be appreciated.

959
01:03:29,840 --> 01:03:34,600
I know you've had dealings with us
before, Mr Foyle, so I'm sure I can
rely on your discretion.

960
01:03:34,880 --> 01:03:38,200
I head up a section here within MI9.

961
01:03:38,200 --> 01:03:40,920
We were established in December '41

962
01:03:40,920 --> 01:03:44,240
to teach evasion and escape
techniques to personnel.

963
01:03:44,240 --> 01:03:47,200
That's ordinary officers and
servicemen heading into action.

964
01:03:47,200 --> 01:03:49,800
There were a series of seminars.
Exactly.

965
01:03:49,800 --> 01:03:53,800
Taught them how to make a nuisance
of themselves if they got caught by
the enemy.

966
01:03:53,800 --> 01:03:58,280
And one vital part of the work was
getting information to us behind
Jerry's back.

967
01:03:58,280 --> 01:04:03,000
Via coded letters. POWs would send
letters to family and friends

968
01:04:03,280 --> 01:04:05,320
and they then forwarded them on
to us.

969
01:04:05,320 --> 01:04:08,240
How many agents were there?

970
01:04:08,240 --> 01:04:10,200
Oh, hundreds of them, all over
Europe.

971
01:04:10,200 --> 01:04:13,480
And how did you communicate
with them? We couldn't.

972
01:04:13,480 --> 01:04:17,520
By the end of the war, we weren't
sure how many of them we had or who
they were.

973
01:04:17,520 --> 01:04:21,680
Our office in Southgate took a
direct hit and many of the records
were destroyed.

974
01:04:21,680 --> 01:04:25,040
So we've had to rely on agents like
Stanford here to get in touch
with us.

975
01:04:26,760 --> 01:04:29,120
And you were a member
of the British Free Corps?

976
01:04:29,120 --> 01:04:31,400
Yes, yes,
it seemed like a good idea.

977
01:04:31,400 --> 01:04:33,760
I thought they might amount to
something.

978
01:04:33,760 --> 01:04:38,040
My aim was to spread discord,
undermine morale and keep MI9 aware
of their movements.

979
01:04:38,040 --> 01:04:41,200
Stanford was afforded a remarkable
degree of freedom.

980
01:04:41,200 --> 01:04:44,000
And thanks to him, we received a
great deal of information

981
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:47,040
about troop movements, bomb damage -
much, much more than that.

982
01:04:48,520 --> 01:04:50,840
What about James Devereaux?

983
01:04:50,840 --> 01:04:54,080
He wasn't like the others, Mr Foyle.

984
01:04:54,080 --> 01:04:56,680
I knew him before the war. We were
at Eton together.

985
01:04:56,680 --> 01:04:59,200
I don't know what he was doing in
the Free Corps

986
01:04:59,200 --> 01:05:03,920
and I'm being completely honest when
I say I feel sorry for him.

987
01:05:03,920 --> 01:05:05,360
Hmm.

988
01:05:05,360 --> 01:05:09,400
Is he a traitor? They all are,
but for different reasons.

989
01:05:09,400 --> 01:05:12,840
My feeling about Devereaux is that
he was out of his depth.

990
01:05:12,840 --> 01:05:15,680
Went missing for a very long time
after Dresden.

991
01:05:15,680 --> 01:05:17,680
What do you think happened to him?

992
01:05:17,680 --> 01:05:20,440
The bombing of Dresden - it's a
dreadful business.

993
01:05:22,320 --> 01:05:24,760
We were in a cafe together when it
started.

994
01:05:24,760 --> 01:05:27,840
We got separated in the street. It
was dark, there was a lot of panic.

995
01:05:27,840 --> 01:05:29,920
I thought he must have been killed.

996
01:05:29,920 --> 01:05:32,320
The city, the next morning, you have
no idea.

997
01:05:33,600 --> 01:05:35,480
So many bodies.

998
01:05:36,400 --> 01:05:40,440
So you knew Agnes Lyttleton?

999
01:05:40,440 --> 01:05:43,440
Yes, yes, she was a friend of mine.
James introduced us.

1000
01:05:43,440 --> 01:05:46,000
As you know, I used her to drop off
my letters.

1001
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:48,080
Did you know she was dead?

1002
01:05:48,080 --> 01:05:51,360
Yes, yes. I read about it in the
papers. Shocking.

1003
01:05:51,360 --> 01:05:54,800
And were you able to see her after
you got back? No.

1004
01:05:54,800 --> 01:05:56,680
The letter, Mr Foyle.

1005
01:05:57,600 --> 01:05:59,520
Oh, yeah.

1006
01:05:59,520 --> 01:06:02,040
No need to remind you that it's
police evidence.

1007
01:06:02,040 --> 01:06:03,760
Of course.

1008
01:06:03,760 --> 01:06:07,760
We have absolutely no intention
of interfering with any police
investigation.

1009
01:06:07,760 --> 01:06:10,200
Well, clearly no intention of
helping it either.

1010
01:06:10,200 --> 01:06:12,400
Well, I don't see it makes much
difference.

1011
01:06:12,400 --> 01:06:14,880
You're no longer a police officer.
Absolutely right.

1012
01:06:14,880 --> 01:06:17,760
It doesn't stop the rest of them
investigating.

1013
01:06:17,760 --> 01:06:19,760
Then I suggest you leave it to them,
Mr Foyle.

1014
01:06:19,760 --> 01:06:21,680
This really isn't your affair.

1015
01:06:22,960 --> 01:06:24,600
Point taken.

1016
01:06:34,680 --> 01:06:36,200
Mr West.

1017
01:06:39,000 --> 01:06:41,480
Perhaps Mr Foyle was wrong
about the settlement.

1018
01:06:41,480 --> 01:06:43,360
Mr Foyle is never wrong.

1019
01:06:47,960 --> 01:06:50,040
MRS RAMSAY:
So there are three of you now?

1020
01:06:50,040 --> 01:06:54,040
Well, Mr Foyle has kindly agreed to
help us with our investigation.

1021
01:06:54,040 --> 01:06:56,440
I'd have thought you'd have caught
him by this time.

1022
01:06:56,440 --> 01:07:01,120
So, why are you here? I told you
everything I know the last time.

1023
01:07:01,120 --> 01:07:03,920
We wondered what the name Jack
might mean to you?

1024
01:07:03,920 --> 01:07:05,240
Jack?

1025
01:07:06,800 --> 01:07:10,120
Jack Stanford.
She never mentioned him?

1026
01:07:10,120 --> 01:07:13,360
No. But the name did seem to mean
something to you just now.

1027
01:07:13,360 --> 01:07:16,600
I did know a Jack. But that was a
long time ago.

1028
01:07:16,600 --> 01:07:18,440
Go on.

1029
01:07:31,360 --> 01:07:32,640
Sh!

1030
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:40,120
Mrs Ramsay,

1031
01:07:40,120 --> 01:07:45,120
I don't suppose you've seen a dark,
dangerous-looking adventurer by the
name of Jack Harkaway, have you?

1032
01:07:45,240 --> 01:07:47,640
No, Lady Devereaux. I've just been
cleaning in here.

1033
01:07:49,440 --> 01:07:51,360
Ah!

1034
01:07:51,360 --> 01:07:53,400
Now, I wonder
where he could be hiding?

1035
01:07:53,400 --> 01:07:55,440
Wait a minute.

1036
01:07:55,440 --> 01:07:58,680
I saw that curtain move.

1037
01:07:59,760 --> 01:08:02,400
Have at you!
I have you, Jack Harkaway.

1038
01:08:02,400 --> 01:08:04,400
My boy, Jack!

1039
01:08:04,400 --> 01:08:06,360
'It's lunch time.
Adventurers must eat.'

1040
01:08:06,360 --> 01:08:08,160
Jack.

1041
01:08:08,160 --> 01:08:10,040
That was her name for him.

1042
01:08:11,400 --> 01:08:13,600
That's what
she always used to call him.

1043
01:08:14,960 --> 01:08:17,200
After the hero in the comic books.

1044
01:08:34,120 --> 01:08:36,040
(KEYS JANGLE)

1045
01:08:43,360 --> 01:08:45,280
(KEY TURNS IN LOCK)

1046
01:08:47,120 --> 01:08:49,640
Why do you keep agreeing to see me?

1047
01:08:49,640 --> 01:08:52,520
To find out
why you keep coming back.

1048
01:08:55,080 --> 01:08:57,520
Presumably this time it's to say
goodbye?

1049
01:08:57,520 --> 01:09:01,920
Far from it. But I do think it's
time we were honest with each other.

1050
01:09:01,920 --> 01:09:03,960
It's certainly time you were honest
with me.

1051
01:09:07,120 --> 01:09:09,040
Has Agnes been to see you?

1052
01:09:10,080 --> 01:09:12,240
How do you know about her?

1053
01:09:13,320 --> 01:09:16,440
Because I know about you...Jack.

1054
01:09:20,080 --> 01:09:22,000
Has she been?

1055
01:09:23,440 --> 01:09:24,720
No.

1056
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:28,920
Do you know why?

1057
01:09:36,880 --> 01:09:39,800
I know what you're doing. Not at all
sure why you're doing it.

1058
01:09:39,800 --> 01:09:42,640
But it's a tragedy you haven't been
able to see the consequences.

1059
01:09:42,640 --> 01:09:45,080
And I think it's time you stopped.

1060
01:09:46,080 --> 01:09:48,000
Because she's dead.

1061
01:09:50,800 --> 01:09:52,400
How?

1062
01:09:52,400 --> 01:09:56,320
She was strangled
at an address in Brighton,

1063
01:09:56,320 --> 01:09:58,280
an address
you'd be very familiar with.

1064
01:10:07,360 --> 01:10:09,280
And you know who did it.

1065
01:10:14,920 --> 01:10:16,840
(VEHICLE ROARS PAST)

1066
01:10:23,200 --> 01:10:27,600
To be honest, Mr Wainwright, I don't
know why you just can't take the
money like everyone else.

1067
01:10:27,600 --> 01:10:30,440
Because it's not just a matter of
money, Mr Harrison. Isn't it?

1068
01:10:30,440 --> 01:10:33,520
How many names did you manage to get
on that petition of yours?

1069
01:10:33,520 --> 01:10:36,360
We got over 200.
200. (LAUGHS)

1070
01:10:36,360 --> 01:10:38,360
The petition is irrelevant.

1071
01:10:38,360 --> 01:10:41,760
You're not building on the green
because there's evidence
of a settlement.

1072
01:10:41,760 --> 01:10:44,400
Because you found a few old coins
and broken lanterns?

1073
01:10:44,400 --> 01:10:46,560
We never mentioned anything about
lanterns.

1074
01:10:49,040 --> 01:10:51,360
But I will tell you
that we found this.

1075
01:10:51,360 --> 01:10:54,840
What is that?
The coins are to pay the ferryman.

1076
01:10:54,840 --> 01:10:59,800
The lanterns light the way to Hades.
And this, as Mr Huntsville has
verified, is a tubulus.

1077
01:11:00,280 --> 01:11:02,920
They poured honey and wine through
it to feed the dead.

1078
01:11:02,920 --> 01:11:07,440
Everything points to there being a
major Roman burial site underneath
Highcliffe green, Mr Harrison.

1079
01:11:07,920 --> 01:11:10,240
So no-one's going to let you
anywhere near it.

1080
01:11:15,440 --> 01:11:19,560
Why? Why did you have to get
involved in all that?

1081
01:11:21,360 --> 01:11:23,520
Don't you believe in progress?

1082
01:11:23,520 --> 01:11:25,640
Progress or profit?

1083
01:11:25,640 --> 01:11:27,480
I think I know
which one you believe in.

1084
01:11:37,880 --> 01:11:40,400
Adam, you were magnificent!
Do you think so?

1085
01:11:40,400 --> 01:11:42,800
It's nothing less than a triumph
for democracy.

1086
01:11:42,800 --> 01:11:45,560
Well, common sense.
And Hill House.

1087
01:11:45,560 --> 01:11:47,720
We could have a fete on the green
to celebrate.

1088
01:11:48,800 --> 01:11:51,200
Yes. What do you think?

1089
01:11:52,080 --> 01:11:54,200
(EXPLOSION)

1090
01:11:54,200 --> 01:11:56,680
That's Hill House.

1091
01:11:56,680 --> 01:11:58,440
Crikey!
Not another bomb!

1092
01:12:01,720 --> 01:12:03,240
Oh!

1093
01:12:03,240 --> 01:12:05,920
No, Adam, wait.
Wait for the fire brigade.

1094
01:12:05,920 --> 01:12:07,800
What about the guests?

1095
01:12:12,520 --> 01:12:14,400
(COUGHING AND SPLUTTERING)

1096
01:12:15,560 --> 01:12:17,600
Are you all right?
Yeah, I'm fine!

1097
01:12:21,440 --> 01:12:26,000
Stay back, Mr Wainwright!
Mr West! Get out of here.

1098
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:28,720
Is there anybody else up there?
I don't think so, don't think so.

1099
01:12:34,200 --> 01:12:35,360
Sam?

1100
01:12:36,240 --> 01:12:38,160
Mrs Crawley!

1101
01:12:38,160 --> 01:12:39,800
Is she all right?

1102
01:12:39,800 --> 01:12:41,840
(FIRE ENGINE BELL)

1103
01:12:41,840 --> 01:12:44,320
She's still got a pulse,
she's still breathing.

1104
01:12:44,320 --> 01:12:46,520
Anybody in there?
MRS CRAWLEY: I can smell gas.

1105
01:12:46,520 --> 01:12:49,080
Anybody here? What the hell are you
doing in here?

1106
01:12:49,080 --> 01:12:52,480
This whole place could collapse at
any moment. It's my hotel!

1107
01:12:52,480 --> 01:12:55,560
We've got someone here who's hurt.
All right, we'll take over now.

1108
01:12:55,560 --> 01:12:57,280
Look, just get out into the street.

1109
01:12:59,520 --> 01:13:02,240
Come on, I've got you now.
Come on, darling.

1110
01:13:04,880 --> 01:13:06,240
Oh, Adam.

1111
01:13:08,680 --> 01:13:11,280
I'm sorry.
I don't know, Sam.

1112
01:13:11,280 --> 01:13:14,520
I never was cut out to run a hotel,
anyway.

1113
01:13:14,520 --> 01:13:16,600
(MRS CRAWLEY GROANS)
There you go.

1114
01:13:16,600 --> 01:13:19,160
What will you do now?
That's it.

1115
01:13:19,160 --> 01:13:21,040
I thought I might marry you.

1116
01:13:23,160 --> 01:13:24,640
What?

1117
01:13:24,640 --> 01:13:27,840
I've got no house, no job, no money
and no future.

1118
01:13:30,360 --> 01:13:32,240
Will you marry me, Sam?

1119
01:13:32,240 --> 01:13:33,960
Adam!

1120
01:13:33,960 --> 01:13:37,000
You'd better hurry up before a wall
falls on top of us.

1121
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:39,240
Come on, you two, out!
Oh.

1122
01:13:39,240 --> 01:13:42,040
All right, yes, I will.
Please get up!

1123
01:13:42,040 --> 01:13:44,320
Do you mean it?
Yes, of course I mean it.

1124
01:13:44,320 --> 01:13:47,160
Of course I'll marry you.
I'll marry you in a shot.

1125
01:13:47,160 --> 01:13:49,040
Sam, that's wonderful.

1126
01:13:51,880 --> 01:13:53,800
(CRASH OF RUBBLE)

1127
01:14:09,720 --> 01:14:11,600
(DOOR OPENS)

1128
01:14:11,600 --> 01:14:15,080
Oh, it's very good news, Sir Charles,
with regards to James.

1129
01:14:15,080 --> 01:14:16,920
What?

1130
01:14:16,920 --> 01:14:19,520
Well, the verdict - that is to say,
the death penalty -

1131
01:14:19,520 --> 01:14:21,520
is certain to be overturned.

1132
01:14:21,520 --> 01:14:23,840
Darling, that's wonderful!

1133
01:14:26,880 --> 01:14:29,880
That's...more
than I could have hoped for.

1134
01:14:29,880 --> 01:14:33,960
But how? How did this happen?

1135
01:14:33,960 --> 01:14:35,840
He decided to speak.

1136
01:14:35,840 --> 01:14:39,240
And though there are various
procedures to go through,

1137
01:14:39,240 --> 01:14:42,360
in the light of what he said,
he'll be released very soon.

1138
01:14:42,360 --> 01:14:43,880
Oh, my goodness.

1139
01:14:43,880 --> 01:14:45,920
Oh, we're...

1140
01:14:45,920 --> 01:14:49,480
We're very grateful to you,
Mr Foyle.

1141
01:14:49,480 --> 01:14:53,960
The only problem is, you'll now
have to account for your part
in all this.

1142
01:14:53,960 --> 01:14:55,680
I don't understand.

1143
01:14:56,680 --> 01:14:59,320
How long had you known Agnes?

1144
01:14:59,320 --> 01:15:01,800
I knew her when we were children.

1145
01:15:03,080 --> 01:15:06,560
Her father worked on the estate.
We used to play together.

1146
01:15:08,520 --> 01:15:10,440
And later?

1147
01:15:10,440 --> 01:15:13,080
You wrote to her, from Germany.

1148
01:15:13,080 --> 01:15:17,400
And she helped pass on coded
information

1149
01:15:17,400 --> 01:15:19,760
in the letters to the intelligence
services,

1150
01:15:19,760 --> 01:15:22,560
which you signed "Jack".

1151
01:15:22,560 --> 01:15:24,440
How do you know all this?

1152
01:15:26,040 --> 01:15:27,960
So you don't deny it?

1153
01:15:30,400 --> 01:15:31,520
No.

1154
01:15:32,880 --> 01:15:34,960
Why "Jack"?

1155
01:15:34,960 --> 01:15:37,120
My mother used to call me Jack.

1156
01:15:39,400 --> 01:15:43,800
It was the name of a character
in a story that I loved as a boy.

1157
01:15:45,960 --> 01:15:48,920
Jack...
Harkaway.

1158
01:15:54,960 --> 01:15:58,240
He joined the British Free Corps to
undermine and to disrupt it

1159
01:15:58,240 --> 01:16:02,280
and used the freedom of movement it
gave him to send reports back to
intelligence here.

1160
01:16:02,280 --> 01:16:04,320
He's a brave young man.

1161
01:16:04,320 --> 01:16:06,280
I knew it.

1162
01:16:06,280 --> 01:16:08,720
I knew he couldn't have been a
traitor.

1163
01:16:08,720 --> 01:16:12,960
Why didn't he say this? Why did it
never come out in the trial?

1164
01:16:12,960 --> 01:16:15,840
Because he wanted to hang,
as a traitor.

1165
01:16:15,840 --> 01:16:18,400
The codes I used
existed in various forms.

1166
01:16:18,400 --> 01:16:22,680
The letter you've mentioned was
written in 56-0, for example.

1167
01:16:22,680 --> 01:16:26,760
Which effectively means you pick out
the fifth and sixth words
of each line.

1168
01:16:26,760 --> 01:16:30,600
And the backward date?
Indicates a concealed code.

1169
01:16:32,160 --> 01:16:36,280
Anyone else in the British Free
Corps know you were doing this?

1170
01:16:37,520 --> 01:16:39,080
Yes, there was.

1171
01:16:40,760 --> 01:16:42,640
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1172
01:16:44,400 --> 01:16:47,600
James, this is yours, I believe.

1173
01:16:48,840 --> 01:16:51,160
Where did you get that?
Agnes Lyttleton?

1174
01:16:51,160 --> 01:16:53,400
You never mentioned a girl.
Give it to me.

1175
01:16:53,400 --> 01:16:57,000
You take a devil of a time writing
these letters. And all those notes
you make.

1176
01:16:57,000 --> 01:17:00,720
If I didn't know you better,
I'd say you were working on some
sort of code.

1177
01:17:01,960 --> 01:17:06,240
Are you, James? Actually, that
would explain a lot of things.

1178
01:17:06,240 --> 01:17:10,000
I wondered what you were doing here,
you of all people. Always asking
questions.

1179
01:17:10,000 --> 01:17:12,040
The first of the bunch to undermine
morale.

1180
01:17:13,920 --> 01:17:17,520
Don't worry. I'm not going to tell
anyone. I'm your friend. You can
trust me.

1181
01:17:22,920 --> 01:17:25,120
But you're a sly old bugger,
aren't you?

1182
01:17:27,440 --> 01:17:29,400
He worked it all out for himself.

1183
01:17:31,280 --> 01:17:33,200
I didn't need to say anything.

1184
01:17:34,680 --> 01:17:38,840
Jack Stanford, I'm arresting you
for the murder of Agnes Lyttleton.

1185
01:17:38,840 --> 01:17:40,880
You don't have to say anything,

1186
01:17:40,880 --> 01:17:44,120
but anything you do say may be
taken down and used in evidence
against you.

1187
01:17:44,120 --> 01:17:45,680
Oh.

1188
01:17:45,680 --> 01:17:48,440
Well, that's a bit annoying,
I must say.

1189
01:17:49,920 --> 01:17:51,960
Really thought
I might get away with it.

1190
01:17:51,960 --> 01:17:55,040
End of the war, all the confusion,
lost records, all the rest of it.

1191
01:17:56,440 --> 01:17:58,320
I don't understand.

1192
01:17:58,320 --> 01:18:01,800
The letters that you were receiving
from Germany weren't from Stanford.

1193
01:18:01,800 --> 01:18:05,120
They were from James Devereaux,
using a childhood nickname.

1194
01:18:05,120 --> 01:18:09,280
When Stanford found out that James
had gone missing, presumed dead,
in Dresden,

1195
01:18:09,280 --> 01:18:12,240
he took over his identity
to save his own neck.

1196
01:18:12,240 --> 01:18:14,400
Is this true?
I thought he was dead.

1197
01:18:14,400 --> 01:18:18,240
It was just a coincidence that he
was using my name, so I thought,
why not?

1198
01:18:18,240 --> 01:18:19,960
Give it a shot.

1199
01:18:21,280 --> 01:18:24,680
But what about this girl? Why would
she have to die?

1200
01:18:24,680 --> 01:18:27,840
She was the only one who knew the
letters had been written by James.

1201
01:18:27,840 --> 01:18:30,960
As soon as the trial began,
she would have come forward.

1202
01:18:30,960 --> 01:18:33,280
So he killed her.

1203
01:18:33,280 --> 01:18:37,760
The moment that James was arrested
and brought home, it was a death
sentence for her.

1204
01:18:37,760 --> 01:18:40,200
Stanford couldn't let her talk.

1205
01:18:40,200 --> 01:18:42,160
There was only one thing to do.

1206
01:18:49,880 --> 01:18:53,120
You took the photograph of James
Devereaux with you,

1207
01:18:53,120 --> 01:18:57,240
the one thing that would have still
identified him as her boyfriend

1208
01:18:57,240 --> 01:18:59,560
and the real author of the letters.

1209
01:19:00,960 --> 01:19:03,320
You're a murderer and a traitor.

1210
01:19:03,320 --> 01:19:06,680
Actually, I only joined the British
Free Corps because I was bored
and hungry.

1211
01:19:06,680 --> 01:19:09,400
I'd had three years as a POW.

1212
01:19:09,400 --> 01:19:12,120
I always knew the whole thing would
be a complete lash-up.

1213
01:19:15,320 --> 01:19:18,520
Why do you find this so funny? I was
just thinking about what you said.

1214
01:19:18,520 --> 01:19:20,720
Murderer and a traitor.

1215
01:19:20,720 --> 01:19:23,880
I suppose it's a shame they can't
hang me twice.

1216
01:19:25,080 --> 01:19:28,480
SIR CHARLES: 'So this man Stanford
was the real traitor.'

1217
01:19:28,480 --> 01:19:30,840
But why did my son
let him get away with it?

1218
01:19:30,840 --> 01:19:33,000
Why didn't he speak out?

1219
01:19:33,000 --> 01:19:36,200
Well, at the time, he was unaware
of Stanford's involvement.

1220
01:19:36,200 --> 01:19:39,840
None of this tells us why he put
himself in that position in the
first place.

1221
01:19:39,840 --> 01:19:43,440
I don't understand. Why would he
want to die?

1222
01:19:43,440 --> 01:19:47,040
There are those far more qualified
than myself to explain
this sort of thing.

1223
01:19:47,040 --> 01:19:49,440
But as far as I understand it,
he went missing

1224
01:19:49,440 --> 01:19:53,680
as a result of the severe nervous
collapse he experienced during the
Dresden bombing,

1225
01:19:53,680 --> 01:19:58,120
itself compounded by the suppressed
traumas suffered in his childhood.

1226
01:20:00,880 --> 01:20:03,320
Would we be talking about the death
of his mother?

1227
01:20:07,060 --> 01:20:08,820
Would we?

1228
01:20:13,920 --> 01:20:17,080
'Why was it so very important
for your father to be at the trial

1229
01:20:17,080 --> 01:20:20,120
when you refused to even see
or speak to him before it?

1230
01:20:22,800 --> 01:20:26,800
And why would he believe that you
want to punish him?

1231
01:20:29,600 --> 01:20:31,520
Because it's true.

1232
01:20:35,560 --> 01:20:37,480
He needs to be.

1233
01:20:37,480 --> 01:20:39,120
Punished?

1234
01:20:40,480 --> 01:20:42,360
Because of your mother?

1235
01:20:46,760 --> 01:20:48,600
I knew her.

1236
01:20:51,880 --> 01:20:54,040
I was injured in the first war.

1237
01:20:54,040 --> 01:20:57,840
Not very badly,
but I was young, alone, frightened.

1238
01:20:59,840 --> 01:21:01,760
She was a volunteer nurse.

1239
01:21:06,400 --> 01:21:08,200
Your mother was beautiful.

1240
01:21:22,360 --> 01:21:24,320
I knew her.

1241
01:21:27,120 --> 01:21:29,520
She was married to my father
at the time?

1242
01:21:34,640 --> 01:21:35,960
Yes.

1243
01:21:38,880 --> 01:21:43,000
I can tell you that she was
desperately unhappy

1244
01:21:43,000 --> 01:21:44,920
with the life she was leading,

1245
01:21:44,920 --> 01:21:48,160
at her happiest when he was away.

1246
01:21:50,960 --> 01:21:54,840
But she chose to pursue that life for
the sake of the child she was
carrying.

1247
01:21:57,120 --> 01:21:58,400
Me.

1248
01:22:23,060 --> 01:22:26,540
The accident that killed her
was just dreadful.

1249
01:22:29,060 --> 01:22:32,020
I was very unhappy to hear
that she died.

1250
01:22:32,020 --> 01:22:33,900
It wasn't an accident.

1251
01:22:47,580 --> 01:22:49,540
They'd had a terrible argument.

1252
01:22:53,060 --> 01:22:56,260
Something about Simon,
my old piano teacher.

1253
01:22:56,260 --> 01:23:00,140
SIR CHARLES: 'You will not humiliate
me and my family...'

1254
01:23:00,140 --> 01:23:02,300
I was in the hide.

1255
01:23:02,300 --> 01:23:04,860
This is the end of it.
He didn't steal anything.

1256
01:23:04,860 --> 01:23:08,020
You had him sent to prison because
he was my friend,

1257
01:23:08,020 --> 01:23:09,980
because he knew how you treated me.

1258
01:23:09,980 --> 01:23:13,100
He's a Jew. He's nothing.
You make me sick, Charles!

1259
01:23:13,100 --> 01:23:15,980
I'm leaving you.
You will not leave me.

1260
01:23:15,980 --> 01:23:19,340
How will you stop me? I'll tell
the whole world what sort of man
you are.

1261
01:23:19,340 --> 01:23:21,540
Get out of my way!
You will not do this.

1262
01:23:21,540 --> 01:23:25,460
You will not leave me.
I will stop you. I will!

1263
01:23:25,460 --> 01:23:27,340
(THUDS AND SCREAMING)

1264
01:24:06,660 --> 01:24:08,820
Dear God, Charles.

1265
01:24:11,620 --> 01:24:13,540
You always said you loved her.

1266
01:24:17,940 --> 01:24:19,300
Charles?

1267
01:24:21,180 --> 01:24:23,100
I couldn't let her walk out on me.

1268
01:24:25,540 --> 01:24:27,660
My family doesn't divorce.

1269
01:24:30,620 --> 01:24:32,620
It's never happened.

1270
01:24:32,620 --> 01:24:34,740
So you killed her.

1271
01:24:38,900 --> 01:24:40,820
And James saw it all.

1272
01:24:43,260 --> 01:24:45,340
That poor little boy.

1273
01:24:53,300 --> 01:24:55,220
(DOOR CLOSES)

1274
01:25:12,420 --> 01:25:14,100
This way, sir.

1275
01:25:31,980 --> 01:25:33,980
Thank you once again, sir.

1276
01:25:33,980 --> 01:25:36,380
Not at all, thank you.

1277
01:25:36,380 --> 01:25:38,860
Well I can't take the credit
for the arrest.

1278
01:25:38,860 --> 01:25:40,740
I don't see why not.

1279
01:25:45,180 --> 01:25:49,180
So, this is goodbye.
Yeah, it looks like it.

1280
01:25:49,180 --> 01:25:51,380
You're on your own now.

1281
01:25:51,380 --> 01:25:54,340
He's got me, sir.
Precisely.

1282
01:25:54,340 --> 01:25:55,980
Good luck.

1283
01:26:05,780 --> 01:26:07,740
What will happen to me now?

1284
01:26:07,740 --> 01:26:09,780
Well, I'd say you'll be released.

1285
01:26:09,780 --> 01:26:11,820
It may take a day or two.

1286
01:26:11,820 --> 01:26:14,140
And I'll be away for a while.

1287
01:26:14,140 --> 01:26:17,380
But, as soon as I'm back, if there's
anything I can do to help...

1288
01:26:22,260 --> 01:26:23,820
Thank you, sir.

1289
01:26:33,180 --> 01:26:35,860
CAROLINE DEVEREAUX:
'Christopher, I'm so sorry.

1290
01:26:35,860 --> 01:26:37,740
I can't see you again

1291
01:26:37,740 --> 01:26:39,740
and I want you to promise

1292
01:26:39,740 --> 01:26:42,980
that you'll never, ever try to
contact me again, whatever happens.

1293
01:26:42,980 --> 01:26:47,380
Now I have to think about the child,
so I'm going back to Charles.

1294
01:26:47,380 --> 01:26:50,060
There's no other way.
You don't know him.

1295
01:26:50,060 --> 01:26:53,700
Please, for the sake of everything
we've been to one another.

1296
01:26:53,700 --> 01:26:55,500
Please...

1297
01:26:55,500 --> 01:26:57,420
forget me.'

1298
01:27:06,660 --> 01:27:08,580
(SHIP'S HORN)

1299
01:27:21,260 --> 01:27:25,900
Thank you. Happy to drive you, sir,
one last time.

1300
01:27:25,900 --> 01:27:27,940
And do let me know when it's going
to happen.

1301
01:27:27,940 --> 01:27:29,820
As soon as possible.

1302
01:27:29,820 --> 01:27:31,900
I'll do my best to get back in time.

1303
01:27:31,900 --> 01:27:35,060
The relatives
are fighting over which church
to have the ceremony in.

1304
01:27:35,060 --> 01:27:37,860
It doesn't help having four vicars
and a bishop in the family.

1305
01:27:37,860 --> 01:27:40,380
And then what?

1306
01:27:40,380 --> 01:27:44,540
I'm thinking of getting into
politics. That business over the
green gave me a taste for it.

1307
01:27:44,540 --> 01:27:47,340
We're going to have lots of children
and spoil them all rotten.

1308
01:27:48,460 --> 01:27:50,540
I'm very pleased to hear it.

1309
01:27:50,540 --> 01:27:51,820
Bye.

1310
01:27:51,820 --> 01:27:54,700
SOLDIER: I'm gonna go and see my
kids, you know.

1311
01:27:54,700 --> 01:27:57,700
"All remaining passengers on the
Queen Mary..."

1312
01:27:57,700 --> 01:28:00,180
Send us a postcard, sir.
I will.

1313
01:28:00,180 --> 01:28:03,860
Good luck!
"..forward gangway, please."

1314
01:28:08,380 --> 01:28:10,300
Let's go, man, let's go.

